{"term":"1967","caseName":"Jones v. Alfred H. Mayer Company","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1967/645","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 01, 1968","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren15/oral_argument_audio/14898","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Number 645, Joseph Lee Jones, et al., Petitioner, versus Alfred H. Mayer Company et al.","start":0,"stop":34.727,"duration":34.73},{"text":"Mr. Liberman.","start":34.727,"stop":36.468,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":36.468,"stop":40.618,"duration":4.15},{"text":"This case arises on a petition for certiorari to the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals on a judgment which simply affirmed a holding by the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Missouri dismissing the amended complaint in these actions for failure to state the cause of action upon which relief can be granted.","start":40.618,"stop":64.786,"duration":24.17},{"text":"Therefore, the facts which are well pleaded in the First Amendment complaints set out in the appendix are the facts which we are dealing with.","start":64.786,"stop":73.437,"duration":8.65},{"text":"These facts alleged that the respondents, a group of related corporations and one individual or developers of a subdivision known Paddock Woods in St. Louis County, Missouri.","start":73.437,"stop":86.681,"duration":13.24},{"text":"They also are developers of adjacent subdivisions known as Paddock Estates, Paddock Meadows, Paddock Hills, and Wedgwood and perhaps some others.","start":86.681,"stop":97.735,"duration":11.05},{"text":"They received permission from various estate agencies to build these divisions including Paddock Woods.","start":97.735,"stop":105.531,"duration":7.8},{"text":"They layout the streets and the sewers and the recreation facilities and various other facilities and then they plot out certain lots and they sell houses and lots to the public.","start":105.531,"stop":119.088,"duration":13.56},{"text":"The method of selling is by buildings and display houses of different types on the -- at the location of the subdivision.","start":119.088,"stop":127.989,"duration":8.9},{"text":"And then the public looks at the display house and the buyer, if he likes one of the houses, will enter into a contract by which the respondents will build a certain house according to the choice of the buyer on a certain lot.","start":127.989,"stop":142.177,"duration":14.19},{"text":"And when it's completed, the transfer of the property is then made.","start":142.177,"stop":147.788,"duration":5.61},{"text":"It's further alleged that the estate in the various governmental subdivisions of the estate are involved with the building of the subdivision both in the approval and the assistance which they give to the builder and from the standpoint of the function -- community functions which they delegate to the builder with respect to the government of this community.","start":147.788,"stop":171.409,"duration":23.62},{"text":"The facts out of this case in particular arose from Mr. and Mrs. Joseph Jones, the petitioners went out to the subdivision and saw a house which they wanted to buy and attempted buy it, and it is alleged that the respondents refused to deal with them or to sell them a house solely because Mr. Jones is a Negro.","start":171.409,"stop":193.1,"duration":21.69},{"text":"The question presented has led to certain refusal solely because of the raise of the prospective buyer is in violation of the law of the United States.","start":193.1,"stop":204.933,"duration":11.83},{"text":"In our brief, this question took two forms, firstly, whether the conduct is prohibited by Section 1978 of the revised statutes 42 U.S.C., Section 1982.","start":204.933,"stop":220.986,"duration":16.05},{"text":"Secondly, whether regardless of the statute on the particular facts of the case due to the nature of the subdivision, the developer would be barred from discriminating in excluding Negroes even without a statute because of the amount of state action which would be involved in the building of the subdivision.","start":220.986,"stop":241.097,"duration":20.11},{"text":"Also in our brief, we broke down the question concerning the statute into its interpretation and as to whether if interpreted as barring this kind of conduct by developer whether that would be a constitutional -- constitutionally valid statute.","start":241.097,"stop":257.757,"duration":16.66},{"text":"Actually, it has been conceded by the respondents that such interpretation would be constitutional and in fact the court below, the Court of Appeals, Judge Blackmun held in his opinion there was a matter of interpretation of the statute rather than a constitutional question.","start":257.757,"stop":275.444,"duration":17.69},{"text":"So, addressing my first -- myself first to the statutory question rather than the constitutional question, we think that the statute by its plain terms bars a builder of a private subdivision from excluding persons from buying and living in that subdivision because of their race.","start":275.444,"stop":296.73,"duration":21.29}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you apply the individual house zoning?","start":296.73,"stop":299.833,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, that question is not before the Court in this case because --","start":299.833,"stop":303.799,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's your view of the statute.","start":303.799,"stop":306.151,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"In my view of the statute, it would apply to an individual house owner as well but of course that and we have here a subdivision developer in which bar make it much broader type of exclusion as it's pointed out in the brief of United States.","start":306.151,"stop":324.021,"duration":17.87},{"text":"The question concerning the interpretation can be looked at from the standpoint of the history and from a standpoint of what the statute says.","start":324.021,"stop":333.677,"duration":9.66},{"text":"The history of the statute is set out at length in the brief filed by the respondents and there's more of it set out in the petitioner's brief, in the amicus brief filed by the United States and in the amicus filed by the group of organizations and by the National Committee against Discrimination in Housing.","start":333.677,"stop":353.776,"duration":20.1},{"text":"We think that the history, it shows abundant awareness on the part of the drafters of this law but it would apply to individual action as well as to action only by the state.","start":353.776,"stop":364.944,"duration":11.17},{"text":"The -- although there are some mentioned in the debates concerning this law of the problem of state action looked at in the historical standpoint.","start":364.944,"stop":379.669,"duration":14.72},{"text":"I do not think you can interpret it as meaning that would only cover state action.","start":379.669,"stop":384.095,"duration":4.43},{"text":"In other words, the Congress at that time was concerned with state action from the standpoint that they have no doubt under the accepted constitutional doctrine in the McCulloch versus Maryland and Prigg versus Pennsylvania that they can do what they wished with respect to controlling the conduct of individuals in violation of constitutional rights.","start":384.095,"stop":407.197,"duration":23.1},{"text":"They were concerned what would happen when the individuals might have some federal legislation on our position to state legislation either permitting or in some cases requiring discriminatory conduct and for this reason, the debates did at times focused on the question of state action and it was resolved that the state law would have to give way to the federal law.","start":407.197,"stop":433.784,"duration":26.59},{"text":"Nevertheless, there's very little in the debates, there's very little even in the quotations of respondent's brief on pages 16 to 19 from which you can make the negative entrance because they were covering what the states might do, they didn't intend to cover what individuals might do.","start":433.784,"stop":452.403,"duration":18.62},{"text":"The -- excuse me.","start":452.403,"stop":456.263,"duration":3.86},{"text":"Regardless, the -- how you that you can't tell what was in the mind of every member of Congress, the debate was certainly lengthy in the interpretation of the statute as applying to individuals was brought out often enough that we can assume that the Congress was aware of the issue and dealt carefully in the language which it chose to adopt to say what it meant.","start":456.263,"stop":481.761,"duration":25.5},{"text":"Now, this statute, originally the Civil Rights Act of 1866 is set out in full of the appendix of petitioner's brief, and looking at the language you might know that the first place has entitled an act to protect all persons in United States in these Civil Rights and furnish the means of their vindication.","start":481.761,"stop":502.938,"duration":21.18},{"text":"It's not entitled an act to prevent the states from discriminating.","start":502.938,"stop":506.902,"duration":3.96},{"text":"It's a positively worded act in its title and in its language itself which has boiled down in Section 1982, it's just of all citizens of the United States shall have the same right in every state and territory as is enjoined by white citizens thereof to inherit purchase, lease, sell, hold and convey real and personal property.","start":506.902,"stop":530.25,"duration":23.35},{"text":"It -- the language emphasizes not the -- what the states may not do and doesn't even refer to that but rather what the right of an individual citizen who wishes to buy and hold property is.","start":530.25,"stop":544.967,"duration":14.72},{"text":"Furthermore, it goes further not even talking about the right itself but the enjoyment of the right.","start":544.967,"stop":550.048,"duration":5.08},{"text":"So, that it would seem from the language itself that we would have to come to the conclusion that they meant that this was not meant to be nearly some sort of negative restriction on what the states or anyone else might do but was supposed to set forth the enjoyment that the right to which people, particularly Negroes, have the right to enjoy.","start":550.048,"stop":583.126,"duration":33.08},{"text":"The statute in question has not received a great deal of interpretation particularly in this Court.","start":583.126,"stop":592.539,"duration":9.41},{"text":"In fact, the only case that really directly deals with these interpretations of the statute is in the case of United States versus Morris which is a District Court case and an old case but it upholds the interpretation of the statute what we would give to it.","start":592.539,"stop":608.897,"duration":16.36},{"text":"As far as the decisions of this Court, the statute has been referred to collaterally in such cases of Buchanan versus Warley and Oyama versus California but it doesn't mention any limiting aspect of the statute.","start":608.897,"stop":628.239,"duration":19.34},{"text":"And there are some other decisions notably the dictum in Hurd versus Hodge which would limit perhaps, from which the limitation can be implied.","start":628.239,"stop":638.73,"duration":10.49},{"text":"We feel that this limitation is not -- have it by way of dictum comes in conflict with the earlier cases dealing with the statute which don't see any implication limiting the statute to state action and which do -- the fact, the earlier cases with respect to other reconstruction Civil Rights legislation, almost all of them refused to make any such interpretation even though in some cases it might have saved the constitutionality of the law.","start":638.73,"stop":673.921,"duration":35.19},{"text":"Furthermore, to the extent that there is any such implied limitation by Hurd versus Hodge, we think that it will resolve more from a constitutional feeling of the Court at that time that there was some constitutional limitation on the statute rather than what the statute was intended.","start":673.921,"stop":692.002,"duration":18.08},{"text":"And in the holdings of this Court in the Katzenbach versus Morgan and United States versus Price and the Guest case, this limiting constitutional interpretation of the power of Congress under the Fourteenth Amendment, Section 5 has been abandoned.","start":692.002,"stop":708.817,"duration":16.82},{"text":"So that any --","start":708.817,"stop":709.867,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, except that this statute was enacted under the aegis of the Thirteenth Amendment, wasn't it?","start":709.867,"stop":714.894,"duration":5.03}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Originally it was enacted under the Thirteenth Amendment and reenacted --","start":714.894,"stop":717.894,"duration":3}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Reenacted after the adoption of the Fourteenth Amendment?","start":717.894,"stop":719.851,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":719.851,"stop":720.686,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And its original passage was under the aegis of the Thirteenth Amendment.","start":720.686,"stop":723.469,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":723.469,"stop":725.769,"duration":2.3},{"text":"I was referring to the force, if any, of the dictum in Hurd versus Hodge which I think was did perhaps imply some limitation due to Fourteenth Amendment construction which I was urging has been abandoned since that time by this Court and in the Guest case and the Price --","start":725.769,"stop":743.724,"duration":17.96}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but this for valid legislation under the Thirteenth Amendment?","start":743.724,"stop":747.784,"duration":4.06},{"text":"This case may why we have to worry about the Fourteenth Amendment in any limitations obtained in it.","start":747.784,"stop":752.794,"duration":5.01}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't -- it's our opinion that we don't have to whether they were really engaged in a question of statutory interpretation.","start":752.794,"stop":759.223,"duration":6.43}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"And the power of Congress under the Thirteenth Amendment to enact this legislation?","start":759.223,"stop":763.162,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":763.162,"stop":764.264,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I gather that the argument on the other side is that when it was reenacted under the Fourteenth Amendment, then by that process it became operative only where the state action, is that the argument?","start":764.264,"stop":782.684,"duration":18.42}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that that implication may have been made in the opinion of the Court of Appeals and I think that argument will be made by the respondents, I think --","start":782.684,"stop":792.319,"duration":9.63}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that's all I'm saying.","start":792.319,"stop":793.504,"duration":1.19},{"text":"That is the argument, isn't it on the other side?","start":793.504,"stop":795.952,"duration":2.45}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, and my answer to it would be that if Congress had intended any such repealer, they certainly would've gone about it in a more direct way rather than reenacting the same statute in the same words verbatim.","start":795.952,"stop":812.252,"duration":16.3},{"text":"A further argument is made with respect to the interpretation of the statute and it is argued in the respondent's brief that there is no appropriate remedy set out for a violation of a statute and I think that this -- if you'll examine Section 3 of a statute it clearly -- Section 3 of the statute is originally enacted, it clearly envisions that remedy may be by a civil suit and pursuant to the ordinary remedies and says to the extent that where the law has not provided sufficient remedies, the state common law can furnish the necessary equitable remedies as they do in all cases involving real property.","start":812.252,"stop":859.527,"duration":47.28}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"What's become of that Section 3 1956 law?","start":859.527,"stop":861.532,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it's -- it becomes Section 1988, it's been rewarded quite a bit but this particular language as to the finding of the remedy under state laws --","start":861.532,"stop":871.169,"duration":9.64}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Section 1988 --","start":871.169,"stop":872.599,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"-- 42 United States Code, Section of 1988.","start":872.599,"stop":876.698,"duration":4.1}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Of Title 42?","start":876.698,"stop":877.813,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"42.","start":877.813,"stop":882.089,"duration":4.28},{"text":"Furthermore, there is real no real difficulty in furnishing a remedy and a case like this involving real property and the Courts of Equity have been doing this for a long time and compared to -- even the reapportionment case or school segregation case, the remedy is quite simple and much within the judicial remedies and functions which are traditional.","start":882.089,"stop":922.526,"duration":40.44},{"text":"In conclusion with respect to the statute, we feel that the language is as broad as can be imagined and actually the opposite interpretation was least the majority free to exclude the minority from any particular county or portion of the county or state in the United States and with the effect that this did have on -- it does have on schools and jobs and voting.","start":922.526,"stop":954.098,"duration":31.57},{"text":"We think that clearly that Congress did not mean that the right to purchase housing or lease housing was to be dependent upon the will of the white majority which at that time after all probably unclosed to 100% of the property.","start":954.098,"stop":970.621,"duration":16.52},{"text":"Turning to the Fourteenth Amendment argument, we argue that on the facts of this case that conceding that we might concede that the statute did not apply and still it would have to be a reversal of the dismissal of the complaint because there are so much state action involved in the building of a subdivision of this type --","start":970.621,"stop":996.093,"duration":25.47}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"On the question of state action, may I ask you whether the record shows whether this land was zoned or a rezoned specifically for the purpose of this development?","start":996.093,"stop":1011.91,"duration":15.82}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think there's anything about that in the record.","start":1011.91,"stop":1015.93,"duration":4.02}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"That is customary I think, usually a tract of land large enough for development of this source has to be initially zoned or has been zoned and then has to be a rezoned to permit this to take place, is that your understanding?","start":1015.93,"stop":1034.457,"duration":18.53}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there's no doubt that it would have to be zoned single family before the developer would consider going in there and building.","start":1034.457,"stop":1043.395,"duration":8.94}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"So, you would assume that this was zoned specifically for this purpose?","start":1043.395,"stop":1048.947,"duration":5.55}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1048.947,"stop":1050.591,"duration":1.64},{"text":"With respect to the state action contention we -- we feel that whether you look at it from what the state has done with respect to the subdivision under the Burton versus Wilmington Parking Authority approach, or whether you look at it from the other approach of the powers that are given to the developer in either case, you would have to find that there's a state and governmental function being exercised which would require the respondents to deal with the property in a nondiscriminatory manner.","start":1050.591,"stop":1084.472,"duration":33.88},{"text":"In other words, they can't set this thing up by calling part of it private action when it's really a public function and avoid the constitutional responsibility.","start":1084.472,"stop":1095.435,"duration":10.96}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Was that basically because of the size?","start":1095.435,"stop":1099.558,"duration":4.12}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"More because of its function Mr. Justice because the fact that number one, from the standpoint of the state does, if they say, “Zone it,” then they operate with the building of roads and the tying in of the old roads.","start":1099.558,"stop":1115.607,"duration":16.05},{"text":"The statutes, by the way, as set out in the appendix to the brief filed by the United States' amicus showing how they have to rename the streets to continue whatever existing roads might be going up to the subdivision.","start":1115.607,"stop":1130.906,"duration":15.3},{"text":"And how they have to get approval as to the various facility, sewers and parks and sidewalks and how they have to satisfy the government that they've taken into account, access to existing schools and highways and so forth.","start":1130.906,"stop":1147.746,"duration":16.84},{"text":"So, that the Government actually, the various departments of the Government have a great deal to say as to have a subdivision built.","start":1147.746,"stop":1155.277,"duration":7.53}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you make that argument with respect to, perhaps if you built a private house?","start":1155.277,"stop":1163.462,"duration":8.18}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Not to the same extent, I don't --","start":1163.462,"stop":1165.177,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's why I ask you this question of zoning.","start":1165.177,"stop":1167.943,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1167.943,"stop":1169.778,"duration":1.84},{"text":"Well, I think with the private house you wouldn't have questions of roads and sewers and parks and that sort of question involved nor would you have provisions in the laws requiring the builder to show how he's -- what measures he's taken to keep up the character of the neighborhood.","start":1169.778,"stop":1191.091,"duration":21.31},{"text":"And encouraging to file a deed of restrictions, which was set forth of course all the really the things equivalent to zonings such as what kind of fences people can have.","start":1191.091,"stop":1204.522,"duration":13.43},{"text":"And -- in other words, in this case, we feel that that power which by ordinarily been a law has been delegated to the builders and they can -- within the deed of restrictions which runs with the property and all the property in the subdivision, they have the right to enforce it by making assessments.","start":1204.522,"stop":1224.326,"duration":19.8},{"text":"And enforcing these assessments on the property owners, if they buy there and they become in effect a governmental authority by virtue of their power under the deed of restrictions governing the subdivision.","start":1224.326,"stop":1237.781,"duration":13.45}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"How large?","start":1237.781,"stop":1238.539,"duration":0.76},{"text":"How many families are there?","start":1238.539,"stop":1241.814,"duration":3.28},{"text":"I read some part of it, it's sort of a thousand people.","start":1241.814,"stop":1245.505,"duration":3.69}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1245.505,"stop":1246.326,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I would like to know how many units are there.","start":1246.326,"stop":1249.743,"duration":3.42}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be approximately 250 units as it was alleged in the complaint perhaps Mr. Treiman can answer --","start":1249.743,"stop":1257.833,"duration":8.09}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Covering --","start":1257.833,"stop":1258.165,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"-- more accurately on how it's worked out.","start":1258.165,"stop":1260.13,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Covering how much territory?","start":1260.13,"stop":1263.339,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not aware of the exact dimensions of a --","start":1263.339,"stop":1267.285,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is that important?","start":1267.285,"stop":1269.465,"duration":2.18}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1269.465,"stop":1270.279,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Or -- or do you or do you not rely on Marsh against Alabama.","start":1270.279,"stop":1274.321,"duration":4.04}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"We do rely in Marsh versus Alabama --","start":1274.321,"stop":1275.887,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well then, what's the size of it?","start":1275.887,"stop":1277.978,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor --","start":1277.978,"stop":1278.021,"duration":0.04}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you know it?","start":1278.021,"stop":1279.727,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"As I say, the size is not set forth in the exact dimension but we feel that the -- more important than the size is the power and the function of this -- of the developers in this case.","start":1279.727,"stop":1293.001,"duration":13.27},{"text":"In other words, I don't think Marsh versus Alabama would be limited as to whether those are a small town or a big town or a medium town, it's a question as to whether they are exercising in this function.","start":1293.001,"stop":1302.356,"duration":9.36}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Does it have to be a town?","start":1302.356,"stop":1306.095,"duration":3.74}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, not necessarily, but -- I mean we say this is the equivalent of a town and of course if there was one person, then it wouldn't be the equivalent of the town but we think that the function is more important than actually the size of a number of lots.","start":1306.095,"stop":1326.978,"duration":20.88},{"text":"It's also set forth in the appendix that with the adjoining subdivisions that it will be a community involving at least 10,000 families I believe also.","start":1326.978,"stop":1339.155,"duration":12.18}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Are -- are there any commercial or industrial areas in this development?","start":1339.155,"stop":1347.525,"duration":8.37}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, not within the development, no.","start":1347.525,"stop":1349.792,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"So, to that extent, it isn't a self-contained economic unit?","start":1349.792,"stop":1352.645,"duration":2.85},{"text":"It's not a “town” in the sense that there was a town in Marsh against Alabama, is that correct?","start":1352.645,"stop":1359.931,"duration":7.29}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would say it's not the town in the sense of Marsh versus Alabama but in the sense of the 110 municipalities in Saint Louis County, you know, it's as much a town as many of them.","start":1359.931,"stop":1370.448,"duration":10.52}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Most of them are bedroom communities, I suppose.","start":1370.448,"stop":1372.419,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1372.419,"stop":1373.638,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"This is -- and then the streets I suppose that this developer had to dedicate a certain amount of this property for street purposes?","start":1373.638,"stop":1381.525,"duration":7.89}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- as I understand in the --","start":1381.525,"stop":1382.717,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"But then, the streets would become public streets and public sidewalks owned by the -- owned not by this developer but by the --","start":1382.717,"stop":1387.419,"duration":4.7}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe the streets become public streets, the sidewalks I'm not sure about.","start":1387.419,"stop":1391.831,"duration":4.41}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Then I suppose there would be assessments on the contiguous owners?","start":1391.831,"stop":1396.037,"duration":4.21}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, for the --","start":1396.037,"stop":1396.328,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that's a standard way of developing.","start":1396.328,"stop":1398.5,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, and there are public recreation areas involved.","start":1398.5,"stop":1402.155,"duration":3.65}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"There's a golf course I guess, and there is --","start":1402.155,"stop":1403.635,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"There's a golf course and bathe and tennis club, but in addition, I think there's open recreation space.","start":1403.635,"stop":1409.086,"duration":5.45}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"But no industrial or commercial area, is that correct?","start":1409.086,"stop":1411.174,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, not within the kind of course.","start":1411.174,"stop":1412.81,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"I seem to recall reading that it is stipulated that there was no federal or estate mortgage money here or guarantees.","start":1412.81,"stop":1423.893,"duration":11.08}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"There -- no -- yes, in other words, the builder has not received a commitment for an FHA or federally insured loan in the subdivision.","start":1423.893,"stop":1435.002,"duration":11.11},{"text":"I -- it's probably irrelevant.","start":1435.002,"stop":1437.306,"duration":2.3},{"text":"I assume that there are certain buyers who have gone in and bought these lots of who've got an FHA loan, but there is no commitment made to the builder or to the respondents to give such loans for Paddock.","start":1437.306,"stop":1449.265,"duration":11.96}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Then he -- there such point that there would be a federal lending function here but it would operate at the level of the buyers.","start":1449.265,"stop":1460.996,"duration":11.73}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, possibly and as I said, there's really no record on that and --","start":1460.996,"stop":1464.884,"duration":3.89}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that would be extraordinary if that were not so, these days?","start":1464.884,"stop":1468.798,"duration":3.91}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1468.798,"stop":1470.615,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Were there any covenants on behalf of the buyers not to sell to Negroes?","start":1470.615,"stop":1475.585,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Not in this record Your Honor, no and I don't believe there are such.","start":1475.585,"stop":1479.431,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Did you say there were recreational centers, there have park out of this area?","start":1479.431,"stop":1483.864,"duration":4.43}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"I think a park -- open land in the nature of playground and park which of course has to be maintained by the subdivision by assessment or --","start":1483.864,"stop":1494.157,"duration":10.29}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Not by the -- not by the community?","start":1494.157,"stop":1496.785,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, by the subdivisions.","start":1496.785,"stop":1498.802,"duration":2.02},{"text":"It's alleged that way.","start":1498.802,"stop":1499.822,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Did I hear -- did you just say there was no federal money?","start":1499.822,"stop":1502.698,"duration":2.88},{"text":"There are some stipulation that no federal money went?","start":1502.698,"stop":1504.9,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the --","start":1504.9,"stop":1505.752,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What I'm looking at is allegation aid at page 9 (a), Paddock Woods is a part of a community provided that leased in part by loans insured by the credit of federal government?","start":1505.752,"stop":1518.698,"duration":12.95}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1518.698,"stop":1519.219,"duration":0.52},{"text":"There some of these others subdivisions --","start":1519.219,"stop":1521.529,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Not the one that we're directly concerned?","start":1521.529,"stop":1523.514,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1523.514,"stop":1523.731,"duration":0.22},{"text":"Well, no.","start":1523.731,"stop":1524.726,"duration":1},{"text":"As I have alleged that the respondents have other subdivisions in a contiguous area there.","start":1524.726,"stop":1532.626,"duration":7.9},{"text":"It where -- in other words, this subdivision is Paddock Woods, but there's also Wedgwood and Paddock Hills and Paddock Estates and some of these older subdivisions did have FHA insurance commitments.","start":1532.626,"stop":1544.709,"duration":12.08}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that isn't -- that isn't for the developer though?","start":1544.709,"stop":1548.871,"duration":4.16}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that's to the developer.","start":1548.871,"stop":1550.134,"duration":1.26},{"text":"If you got a commitment from the FHA that's made to the developer that they wasn't --","start":1550.134,"stop":1553.612,"duration":3.48}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"but it wasn't -- that wasn't in this case?","start":1553.612,"stop":1555.544,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Not in Paddock Woods, I'll reserve the rest of my time.","start":1555.544,"stop":1574.432,"duration":18.89}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Attorney General?","start":1574.432,"stop":1577.15,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":1577.15,"stop":1585.196,"duration":8.05},{"text":"The United States has asked for this opportunity appears friend of the court because of its very great concern that the rights here involved be fully secured and fulfilled for all of our people.","start":1585.196,"stop":1606.053,"duration":20.86},{"text":"The questions presented are whether the Fourteenth Amendment or Section 1978 of the revised statutes prohibit a developer of a large suburban community from refusing to sell homes within that community to Negroes solely on account of their race.","start":1606.053,"stop":1631.125,"duration":25.07},{"text":"Our concern with these issues arises from the fact that it is the experience of this decade that of all discriminations, the most harmful in and of itself and in its reinforcement of other discriminations is the discrimination that has caused segregation in our living which is primarily discrimination in the sale of housing.","start":1631.125,"stop":1668.501,"duration":37.38},{"text":"Segregate living makes it seems almost impossible in fulfillment of rights secured by the Constitution such as schooling, where in the first five years of this decade, we have witnessed in major metropolitan school districts a vast increase in percentage of Negro students.","start":1668.501,"stop":1697.655,"duration":29.15},{"text":"As an illustration, Chicago has risen from 40% to 52% Negro in the public schools.","start":1697.655,"stop":1704.442,"duration":6.79},{"text":"In Baltimore, the figure has risen from 50% to 61%.","start":1704.442,"stop":1710.062,"duration":5.62},{"text":"In Saint Louis, the principal city in the area from which this case comes, Negro school population in public schools had risen from 49% to 60%.","start":1710.062,"stop":1719.995,"duration":9.93},{"text":"These arise in large measure because of segregation in housing.","start":1719.995,"stop":1726.785,"duration":6.79},{"text":"It's not just in schooling, it's in communications, people in these isolated and alienated areas can hardly be communicated with by itenerants or others.","start":1726.785,"stop":1739.537,"duration":12.75},{"text":"It must be reached our people who lived among them.","start":1739.537,"stop":1743.508,"duration":3.97},{"text":"Same as true to the employment, for vital government services of recreation and of health.","start":1743.508,"stop":1751.468,"duration":7.96},{"text":"The present very substantial and growing urban segregation is caused and maintained in major part by discrimination in sales of housing.","start":1751.468,"stop":1761.602,"duration":10.13},{"text":"Between 1950 and 1960, nonwhite families in unsound urban housing increased 25% from 1.4 million to 1.8 million.","start":1761.602,"stop":1778.591,"duration":16.99},{"text":"In this same decade, nonwhite families and overcrowded urban housing increased 40% from 700,000 to a million families.","start":1778.591,"stop":1790.99,"duration":12.4},{"text":"Among those families earning $10,000 or more a year, 15% of the nonwhite families live in substandard housing compared to 3.7% for white families of comparable income.","start":1790.99,"stop":1808.951,"duration":17.96},{"text":"In 1960, 46% of our nonwhite urban population lived in unsound housing compared to 14% for the whites.","start":1808.951,"stop":1821.737,"duration":12.79},{"text":"I would like to devote my argument primarily to the constitutional issue that in anyway indicating that the United States does not have full confidence that the conduct here involved was prohibited as well by Section 1978 for Title 42.","start":1821.737,"stop":1846.998,"duration":25.26},{"text":"The history of the Fourteenth Amendment clearly reveals that a basic purpose of that Amendment was securing full rights to own, use and dispose of property.","start":1846.998,"stop":1867.282,"duration":20.28},{"text":"The first Section of the Civil Rights Act of 19 -- of 1866 was this statute that we're dealing with today.","start":1867.282,"stop":1877.839,"duration":10.56},{"text":"Contemporaneous with its enactment by the same session of the same Congress, the Congress sent the Fourteenth Amendment to the people for ratification.","start":1877.839,"stop":1887.775,"duration":9.94},{"text":"It was concerned at that time that the property rights sought to be secured by the statute enacted that year to be preserved also by constitutional right.","start":1887.775,"stop":1900.379,"duration":12.6},{"text":"This, have been recognized in the early Slaughter-House Cases as well in Shay -- in Shelley v. Kraemer.","start":1900.379,"stop":1906.039,"duration":5.66},{"text":"The rights of the property were looked upon is precondition to nearly all other rights into their exercise and perhaps the most fundamental of our rights.","start":1906.039,"stop":1916.997,"duration":10.96},{"text":"The Fourteenth Amendment by its own force condemns this discrimination because of the involvement of the states in its effectuation.","start":1916.997,"stop":1931.523,"duration":14.53},{"text":"As early as 1917 in Buchanan v. Warley, the Supreme Court stuck -- or struck a statute, the City of Louisville an ordinance, which restricted the sale of property within a city block to a member of the black race or the white race if his race was not a majority within that block.","start":1931.523,"stop":1958.355,"duration":26.83},{"text":"This was before a separate and equal doctrine was disapproved in such areas of schooling in transportation.","start":1958.355,"stop":1970.568,"duration":12.21},{"text":"But here, the potential for fencing out is much greater than the statute or that ordinance struck in the Buchanan case which reached only a city block.","start":1970.568,"stop":1980.913,"duration":10.35},{"text":"Here, the potential is to hundred of thousands of single family dwellings built within major subdivisions in the United States each year.","start":1980.913,"stop":1990.526,"duration":9.61},{"text":"A major part of our new housing market setting at the very beginning, a pattern of discrimination that can be assume and will persist for many years.","start":1990.526,"stop":2003.105,"duration":12.58},{"text":"The fact of the conduct of respondents here is just fully contrary to the public interest, that was the affect of the ordinance of the City of Louisville, restricted in Buchanan case.","start":2003.105,"stop":2019.905,"duration":16.8},{"text":"And it is as much the state acting as was the act of the city there.","start":2019.905,"stop":2027.205,"duration":7.3},{"text":"In Shelley v. Kraemer in 1948, this Court held that the state cannot enforce private agreements to restrict the sale of property.","start":2027.205,"stop":2041.957,"duration":14.75},{"text":"There, only a handful of properties need be involved.","start":2041.957,"stop":2049.886,"duration":7.93},{"text":"I believe in the record in that case there were 21 separate property ownerships placed under the restrictive covenant that was stricken down.","start":2049.886,"stop":2062.225,"duration":12.34},{"text":"Here, again the fencing out of the Negro is much greater and the action of the state in supporting and enabling and giving the opportunity to the developer to bring this about ever been that great is the involvement of the Court in Shelley v. Kraemer or it was sought to enforce a restrictive covenant.","start":2062.225,"stop":2090.326,"duration":28.1}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any evidence in this record that this private development had been promoted by the state to relieve itself of limitations without the issue of the state or community?","start":2090.326,"stop":2106.851,"duration":16.53}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"For that purpose of causing discrimination, then it could not set itself.","start":2106.851,"stop":2110.268,"duration":3.42},{"text":"I'm not aware of any such evidence or implication in the record to that effect Mr. Justice.","start":2110.268,"stop":2122.429,"duration":12.16},{"text":"In Evans v. Newton in 1966, this Court held that services rendered by a private board of trustees and providing a park service pursuant to the will of Senator Bacon of Georgia, in Macon, Georgia where municipal in nature and that this mere park service was so impregnated with government activity that state action was involved in discrimination in the use of the park was prohibited by the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment.","start":2122.429,"stop":2168.191,"duration":45.76},{"text":"Here, in Paddock Woods, their parks, tennis courts, bathing facilities, all of which will be subject to the restriction against race that is created for this entire suburban community.","start":2168.191,"stop":2189.116,"duration":20.93},{"text":"In Burton v. Wilmington Parking Authority in 1961, the Court in viewing all of the circumstances of the financing and construction of a parking lot in Wilmington and the provision thereof -- by lease from an estate of a private restaurant, held that the state was involved in the discrimination.","start":2189.116,"stop":2212.941,"duration":23.82},{"text":"Even though the restaurant there under those circumstances was operated and maintained by private company and in perhaps the most important and closely relevant case, in Marsh v. Alabama in 1946, the Supreme Court held that a company town, which was owned by Gulf Shipbuilding Corporation, built presumably for furthering the purposes of that corporation in building ships, could not limit the exercise of constitutional rights within that town merely because of the combination of property interest that it there owned.","start":2212.941,"stop":2260.305,"duration":47.36},{"text":"Far less extensive, in our present environment is the company town compared to the subdivision developments with which we're here confronted which make up perhaps most of new suburbia which surrounds our central city ghettos where so many of our minorities are confined and unable regardless of their economic ability to break loose.","start":2260.305,"stop":2293.834,"duration":33.53},{"text":"The pattern of segregation created in these subdivisions will have exactly the same effect that it would have if they were created by act of a legislature or by act of a city council.","start":2293.834,"stop":2314.502,"duration":20.67},{"text":"In regardless of the ownership of the property involved, the public interest must be identical.","start":2314.502,"stop":2320.666,"duration":6.16},{"text":"Here, Paddock Woods is legally indistinguishable from the company of town in Chickasaw, Alabama.","start":2320.666,"stop":2331.096,"duration":10.43},{"text":"It has to go to government, the county government of Saint Louis, the state government of Missouri for all of its powers.","start":2331.096,"stop":2344.774,"duration":13.68},{"text":"It could not provide what it provides for the people without the approval, without the responsibility of state government in doing so.","start":2344.774,"stop":2357.057,"duration":12.28},{"text":"It must provide to the people their streets, sidewalks, water, sewage, park facilities as indicated.","start":2357.057,"stop":2366.568,"duration":9.51},{"text":"It has the power under municipal ordinance of the County of Saint Louis to provide the zoning restrictions through deeds of record.","start":2366.568,"stop":2376.83,"duration":10.26},{"text":"And the nature of these restrictions by usage, and as can be seen from the ordinance itself, go even to noxious conduct of the people resident in the area.","start":2376.83,"stop":2389.848,"duration":13.02}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Mr. Attorney General, what's the authority that you impose -- the assessments for what purpose?","start":2389.848,"stop":2397.042,"duration":7.19}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The -- the authority for -- no, the authority for this is to provide the opportunity for the people within this area to the -- let me put this way the --","start":2397.042,"stop":2418.863,"duration":21.82}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what I have -- this particular reference too is we're told in the brief of the petitioners, the Board of Trustees appointed by the developers as the power to levy assessments against the residents, the communitywide services and maintenance of community facilities and areas and to enforce them through liens in court proceedings.","start":2418.863,"stop":2439.711,"duration":20.85}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that's correct and that's for necessary improvements --","start":2439.711,"stop":2442.31,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What's -- for what?","start":2442.31,"stop":2444.925,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's for necessary improvements or work done for the community.","start":2444.925,"stop":2448.81,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"With that the -- the owner of this corporate area may what?","start":2448.81,"stop":2452.444,"duration":3.63},{"text":"Pave a street and impose assessments against the --","start":2452.444,"stop":2456.135,"duration":3.69}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Paddock Woods can repair the streets, they can beautify park, they can put in trees along the streets, they can lay new sidewalks out and they can assess the property owners to pay for the cost of it.","start":2456.135,"stop":2466.058,"duration":9.92}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And this is a continuing operation in the sense that the Board of Trustees survived the sale of all the houses in the subdivision.","start":2466.058,"stop":2474.564,"duration":8.51}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's --","start":2474.564,"stop":2474.771,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- an ongoing entity, isn't it right?","start":2474.771,"stop":2476.124,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Mr. Justice White.","start":2476.124,"stop":2477.6,"duration":1.48},{"text":"The purpose here goes beyond the mere creation of the community.","start":2477.6,"stop":2481.365,"duration":3.76},{"text":"It goes on to the continuing service.","start":2481.365,"stop":2483.646,"duration":2.28},{"text":"The basic powers of zoning that I -- that I described are set out in page 82 of the government's brief where the municipal ordinance 1005.130 is set forth.","start":2483.646,"stop":2496.425,"duration":12.78},{"text":"And it provides --","start":2496.425,"stop":2497.996,"duration":1.57}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry, I didn't catch that page.","start":2497.996,"stop":2499.816,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It begins on page 82 and goes onto page 83.","start":2499.816,"stop":2502.225,"duration":2.41}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I do.","start":2502.225,"stop":2503.663,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It provides the powers of subdivision, allowed to subdivide -- or divider -- free in the arrangement of streets and lots, at the same time protect the convenience, health, welfare and safety of the probable feature residents of the subdivisions as well as the character of the surrounding property and the general welfare of the entire area.","start":2503.663,"stop":2524.006,"duration":20.34},{"text":"And the practices under that are set out back in about page 17 of our brief which includes the placement of temporary structures on property, the prevention of using property for commercial purposes, and the control of obnoxious personal activities of individuals.","start":2524.006,"stop":2544.679,"duration":20.67}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that the power that they give to the Board of Trustees selected by the developers for the purpose of reliving the state or the community of the responsibility for keeping the streets, and repair, and so forth?","start":2544.679,"stop":2564.36,"duration":19.68}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It's for that purpose Mr. Chief Justice as well as for -- this is a non-incorporated area.","start":2564.36,"stop":2570.759,"duration":6.4},{"text":"It's for purposes of saying that the other -- properties are not damaged by the use to which this property is put.","start":2570.759,"stop":2579.527,"duration":8.77},{"text":"Paddock Woods qualifies as a city of the fourth class under the laws of the State of Missouri and it could, if it chose, to be a city of the fourth class under those laws and engaged in the same activities as a city of the fourth class rather than as a private corporation.","start":2579.527,"stop":2601.28,"duration":21.75}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I notice that page 17 of your brief, Mr. Attorney General on the footnote, you call the Saint Louis County Ordinance, is this what you have reference to?","start":2601.28,"stop":2612.66,"duration":11.38},{"text":"Where the subdivision contain sewers, sewage treatment plants, water supply systems, park areas, street areas or other physical facilities necessary or desirable for the welfare of the area or that of common use or benefit which are not -- which are not or cannot be satisfactory maintained by any existing public agency, provision shall be made by trust agreements and so forth, is that it?","start":2612.66,"stop":2636.698,"duration":24.04}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, sir, that's it.","start":2636.698,"stop":2637.859,"duration":1.16},{"text":"The preceding part is --","start":2637.859,"stop":2641.707,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Provides decree --","start":2641.707,"stop":2642.126,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The other end point here too.","start":2642.126,"stop":2643.457,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2643.457,"stop":2644.026,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"This section is the same section that I refer to in page 82 and 83 of the appendix to this brief.","start":2644.026,"stop":2656.058,"duration":12.03},{"text":"The Court held in Marsh v. Alabama that a Jehovah's Witness could not be prohibited because of the Equal Protection Clause for the Fourteenth Amendment from going into a company town that was concededly private property from going on the sidewalks there and endeavoring to communicate with the people who live there.","start":2656.058,"stop":2686.082,"duration":30.02},{"text":"And if -- and the Court held that the mere fact that this was private property that this is a company of town or rather than ordinary city could not deprive the inhabitants there of their constitutional rights to this sort of communications or the rights of people who did not live there to come there and so communicate.","start":2686.082,"stop":2706.041,"duration":19.96},{"text":"It would seem ironic indeed if this communication could not be prohibited, this casual itenerant communication, but that the very right, the fundamental right to live there, to buy there, to own property there could be prohibited as to the whole area fencing out an entire race.","start":2706.041,"stop":2732.82,"duration":26.78},{"text":"This would seem to me that if its government action within the limits of the property of the company town in Chickasaw, Alabama, for purposes of Jehovah's Witnesses coming on the sidewalks that are private property, then it must be government action also for that corporation and the disposition of its property when it endeavors to restrict its sales to people of the white race.","start":2732.82,"stop":2766.815,"duration":33.99},{"text":"The activities of the city in Marsh v. Alabama are not essentially different from the activities of this suburban community.","start":2766.815,"stop":2786.535,"duration":19.72},{"text":"Here, fire protection has to be provided.","start":2786.535,"stop":2789.267,"duration":2.73},{"text":"Here streets and all the utilities had to be laid out.","start":2789.267,"stop":2793.118,"duration":3.85},{"text":"Here, the purpose was to dispose a property but they have an ongoing entity for its regulation, for its use, and for its enjoyment and that by definition almost, must be government action.","start":2793.118,"stop":2814.152,"duration":21.03},{"text":"We would urge to the Court to hold that when a subdivision in a community involving these many people, alleged to be a thousand people in Paddock Woods alone, in a total development of 2,700 families endeavors to screen out, to fence out all Negroes that it is denying equal protection of the laws in a fundamentally governmental activity violating constitutional rights of the person so-discriminated against.","start":2814.152,"stop":2855.008,"duration":40.86},{"text":"The statute itself, Section 1978 is in the broadest of language.","start":2855.008,"stop":2867.779,"duration":12.77},{"text":"It is clearly language that is supportable by Section 5 of the Fourteenth Amendment.","start":2867.779,"stop":2878.481,"duration":10.7},{"text":"The language designed to prevent the discrimination against Negroes, and the sale and the use and the disposition of property, and if they can be screened out from the whole area here, a whole community involving hundreds of families, then clearly they are denied the rights the statute was designed to protect.","start":2878.481,"stop":2905.3,"duration":26.82},{"text":"The fact that the statute played partially dormant for many years, it cannot be held to diminish its force today any more than Sections 241 and 242, enacted shortly after this were diminished.","start":2905.3,"stop":2927.03,"duration":21.73},{"text":"When it first came before the Court in U.S. v. Classic after 75 years of virtual dormancy, the statute is vital and it's important.","start":2927.03,"stop":2936.804,"duration":9.77},{"text":"There is before the Congress, as the Court knows, legislation that would provide open housing rights on a complicated statutory scheme including administrative judicial and other sanctions for its effectuation.","start":2936.804,"stop":2959.815,"duration":23.01}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is its reach as broad as 1982?","start":2959.815,"stop":2966.816,"duration":7}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Its potential for effectiveness is probably much greater than 1978 because of the sanctions and the remedies that it provides.","start":2966.816,"stop":2978.204,"duration":11.39},{"text":"It approaches the securing of these rights on a graduated basis.","start":2978.204,"stop":2985.208,"duration":7},{"text":"In its ultimate reach, it has three exceptions; single-family dwellings and Mrs. Murphy situation where there is a unit with more than four different families living within it and religious club uses.","start":2985.208,"stop":3003.808,"duration":18.6}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Which exceptions are not in 1978 (Voice Overlap) --","start":3003.808,"stop":3005.768,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Which exceptions that are not in 1978, but it would depend on how you interpreted 1978.","start":3005.768,"stop":3010.704,"duration":4.94}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Attorney General, if that statute becomes law, would it be available to these petitioners?","start":3010.704,"stop":3017.889,"duration":7.18}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It would be if -- it would depend upon the form.","start":3017.889,"stop":3022.378,"duration":4.49},{"text":"The -- the bill that passed the Senate would provide some relief for these petitioners if it became law as of December 31, 1968.","start":3022.378,"stop":3036.615,"duration":14.24},{"text":"It would not seem that it would provide anything like all of the relief that they are entitled to.","start":3036.615,"stop":3042.23,"duration":5.62},{"text":"They first sought a home beginning in February 1965, a first endeavor to buy a particular home in Paddock Woods in June of 1965.","start":3042.23,"stop":3053.251,"duration":11.02},{"text":"It is most probable that property values have increased substantially there and perhaps the people here from Saint Louis can tell you more about that.","start":3053.251,"stop":3062.081,"duration":8.83},{"text":"There has been a loss of time and there have been other damages arising to the petitioner here that cannot be fully atoned for by any new federal legislation.","start":3062.081,"stop":3076.057,"duration":13.98}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you say revised statutes 1978 was a -- is sustainable under Section 5 of Fourteenth Amendment, and I take if the statute -- or the bill before the Congress is pursuant to the same authority?","start":3076.057,"stop":3093.527,"duration":17.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The --","start":3093.527,"stop":3095.011,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Or at least --","start":3095.011,"stop":3095.683,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a --","start":3095.683,"stop":3095.803,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that's one of the basis?","start":3095.803,"stop":3097.501,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's one of the basis also, the Commerce Clause and --","start":3097.501,"stop":3099.612,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Now --","start":3099.612,"stop":3099.705,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- our testimony, we put it on both --","start":3099.705,"stop":3101.551,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"If that statute passes, what will be the relationship between that statute in R.S. 1978?","start":3101.551,"stop":3110.156,"duration":8.61},{"text":"Will 1978 be thereby amended in effect?","start":3110.156,"stop":3115.803,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I would assume that 1978 would stand independently, I would assume as practical matter, the executive branch would move to enforce the new statute, the Department of Housing and Urban Development has substantial powers there even though they're maybe primarily in the area of conciliation.","start":3115.803,"stop":3137.342,"duration":21.54}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And so, its 1978, would it -- would reach single-family situations and the other statute would -- with its administrative remedies would reach all except -- the exceptions?","start":3137.342,"stop":3149.023,"duration":11.68}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"We don't know whether 1978 would reach the single family dwelling or not.","start":3149.023,"stop":3154.239,"duration":5.22},{"text":"The Court doesn't have to hold that here and a court has not at this time held that.","start":3154.239,"stop":3159.01,"duration":4.77}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if you put a straight line, if you press these decisions strictly on the statute, what would you say then?","start":3159.01,"stop":3168.848,"duration":9.84}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I'd say it depend upon the interpretation that the Court placed on the statute.","start":3168.848,"stop":3173.302,"duration":4.45},{"text":"Although, the language is very broad, it does not necessarily have to be construed as reaching -- the concern is not before this Court, whether it would reach the single-family sale.","start":3173.302,"stop":3183.453,"duration":10.15},{"text":"As a matter of proof --","start":3183.453,"stop":3183.764,"duration":0.31}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"How would you --","start":3183.764,"stop":3184.494,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"-- those cases are very difficult too because there are many reasons that you can engage in a single sale that do not necessarily relate -- in relation with race, it would exclude race.","start":3184.494,"stop":3194.405,"duration":9.91}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"How would exclude the single-family situation if you rested this decision, if the decision was in the petitioner's favor and it rested solely on 1978?","start":3194.405,"stop":3206.103,"duration":11.7}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it would be up to the next case to determine whether the Court in this case held.","start":3206.103,"stop":3213.403,"duration":7.3}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what would be the theory for excluding single family --","start":3213.403,"stop":3216.731,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The theories could be several and it would just whether 1978 involves substantial discriminations, whether are single transaction among private parties --","start":3216.731,"stop":3229.12,"duration":12.39}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Certainly, this must be true when those words were put together in 1866, many properties except single-family housing.","start":3229.12,"stop":3241.066,"duration":11.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's --","start":3241.066,"stop":3241.864,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"William J. Brennan, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"On -- on the face of the statute, wouldn't it be rather hard to if this decision would turn only on the statute?","start":3241.864,"stop":3248.298,"duration":6.43},{"text":"Would it be difficult to exclude single-family houses?","start":3248.298,"stop":3252.423,"duration":4.13}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the best reading of the statute would to be to include single-family housing.","start":3252.423,"stop":3255.83,"duration":3.41},{"text":"It might not necessarily cover isolated sales however.","start":3255.83,"stop":3259.627,"duration":3.8},{"text":"It would be very difficult to apply to isolated sales to show intent among other things.","start":3259.627,"stop":3266.41,"duration":6.78},{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":3266.41,"stop":3267.069,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Attorney General.","start":3267.069,"stop":3275.325,"duration":8.26},{"text":"Mr. Treiman.","start":3275.325,"stop":3277.261,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, may it please the Court.","start":3277.261,"stop":3281.957,"duration":4.7},{"text":"I have a -- so we've got seven minutes left.","start":3281.957,"stop":3285.512,"duration":3.56},{"text":"I don't know just where to begin with.","start":3285.512,"stop":3288.056,"duration":2.54},{"text":"The Court has already touched through its questioning on what I believe are some of the most sensitive areas in this entire case especially the questions directed by Mr. Justice White at the very end which I think clearly indicate the profound complications and the very troublesome problems and difficulties that will arise inevitably if this Court should construe Section 1982 as the petitioners and the government and the amici wanted to.","start":3288.056,"stop":3329.019,"duration":40.96},{"text":"I, speaking of the amici, may it please the Court in the few minutes that I have left, I should like to make few general observations as Your Honors have probably observed.","start":3329.019,"stop":3343.584,"duration":14.57},{"text":"There are great many amici briefs that have been filed in this case in support of the petitioners and I must confess that when these briefs started coming to my office I was not a little shaken.","start":3343.584,"stop":3354.961,"duration":11.38},{"text":"And it wasn't -- it wasn't because -- I was disturbed over the fact that with all these many organizations and fine lawyers on one side, I was being left in a somewhat friendless position in this courtroom.","start":3354.961,"stop":3371.191,"duration":16.23},{"text":"I've become sort of accustomed to that back home where even some of my good friends were beginning to look upon me as if I had suddenly become afflicted with leprosy.","start":3371.191,"stop":3383.083,"duration":11.89},{"text":"What disturbed me, may it please the Court, what gave me real concern was how I was suppose to deal with all of these good briefs and they are excellent briefs especially the two that have been mentioned here.","start":3383.083,"stop":3398.902,"duration":15.82},{"text":"The -- I'm talking now but the amici briefs, one by the government and the other by group of national organizations headed by one that calls itself the National Committee against Discrimination in Housing, which I shall refer to as I have in my brief as the NCADH brief.","start":3398.902,"stop":3420.276,"duration":21.37},{"text":"And speaking of that brief, may it please the Court, with reference to the statements made by the honorable Attorney General, in regard to the effect that segregation, racial segregation has had upon the life of our country, I want to say here and now, personally I bow to nobody when it comes to concern over the plight of the disadvantaged Negro family.","start":3420.276,"stop":3455.4,"duration":35.12},{"text":"And may I have this, I have read many articles and books on this subject, but as I told the person who I believe was the principal writer of the NCADH brief, I have now seen anywhere a more powerful, a more eloquent description of the terrible -- the terrible condition in plight in which not only the children but the adults of the Negro families find themselves by reason of their difficulty in obtaining decent housing.","start":3455.4,"stop":3489.986,"duration":34.59},{"text":"So that as to that part of the Attorney General's argument, as far as that part is concern, I assure the Court that I do not quarrel either with the Attorney General or with any of these good friends of the Court who come into this case.","start":3489.986,"stop":3508.87,"duration":18.88},{"text":"What disturbs me, Your Honors, is the way in which they think this problem should be solved.","start":3508.87,"stop":3518.962,"duration":10.09},{"text":"And I must say, since I will have only a minute, as I came into the courtroom this morning for the first time, I saw the words that are inscribed over the portals of this courthouse “equal justice under law.”","start":3518.962,"stop":3536.431,"duration":17.47},{"text":"I must confess my ignorance, I did not know those words were there.","start":3536.431,"stop":3541.08,"duration":4.65},{"text":"And it struck me that this perhaps goes to the very heart of this case surely nobody would deny equal justice under the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment or under Section 1982.","start":3541.08,"stop":3559.291,"duration":18.21},{"text":"But the other two words are just as important, it seems to me.","start":3559.291,"stop":3563.276,"duration":3.98},{"text":"It must be under law.","start":3563.276,"stop":3566.219,"duration":2.94},{"text":"I happen to be a practicing lawyer back home and not a lawyer who assure you, Your Honors, professors to have any great knowledge about constitutional law.","start":3566.219,"stop":3577.511,"duration":11.29},{"text":"I happen to be what people referred to as the bread and butter type of practicing lawyer.","start":3577.511,"stop":3584.981,"duration":7.47},{"text":"And while I have that deep sympathy for the conditions that have been described caused by the acute problems of housing, I am also a practicing lawyer.","start":3584.981,"stop":3597.779,"duration":12.8},{"text":"I have an equal reverence for the orderliness of the law.","start":3597.779,"stop":3604.528,"duration":6.75},{"text":"And I believe Your Honors that if we are to meet this problem, let us meet it in a way that it's provided for under our Constitution and under our philosophy of the meaning of law.","start":3604.528,"stop":3619.068,"duration":14.54},{"text":"It's 2:30 and if I may I should like to close and reserve my time unless the Court wishes to ask me questions.","start":3619.068,"stop":3628.621,"duration":9.55}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll recess now.","start":3628.621,"stop":3629.931,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":3629.931,"stop":3636.263,"duration":6.33}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - April 02, 1968","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/warren15/oral_argument_audio/15041","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Joseph Lee Jones et al., versus Alfred H. Mayer Company et al.","start":0,"stop":9.713,"duration":9.71},{"text":"Mr. Treiman, you may continue with your argument.","start":9.713,"stop":15.006,"duration":5.29}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":15.006,"stop":20.235,"duration":5.23},{"text":"I should like to pass now as quickly as possible to what I regard as the pivotal points of this case.","start":20.235,"stop":32.952,"duration":12.72},{"text":"And I should like to consider those points in two categories corresponding to the two grounds on which the petitioners and the major briefs, that is the Government brief and the NCADH brief, and I must say two or three others, claimed that the District Court was wrong in dismissing the claim.","start":32.952,"stop":62.219,"duration":29.27},{"text":"And that the petitioners are entitled to recover on the basis of the allegations set forth in their complaint.","start":62.219,"stop":70.252,"duration":8.03},{"text":"Now, taking up the first claim, the first ground, which has to do with this Civil Rights Act of 1866 or rather that portion of it which appears today in Section 1982 of Title 42 of United States Code which incidentally the Government and its brief refers to by its revised statute designation of Section 1978.","start":70.252,"stop":100.516,"duration":30.26},{"text":"Here, Your Honors, we deal with a question of pure statutory construction.","start":100.516,"stop":109.398,"duration":8.88},{"text":"And I should like to emphasize that, particularly in view of the question that I believe Mr. Justice Fortas asked of counsel for the petitioners yesterday.","start":109.398,"stop":119.822,"duration":10.42},{"text":"Mr. Justice Fortas, as I recall asked counsel who was then discussing, I believe the constitutionality of this Section under the Thirteenth Amendment whether one could not presume that the respondents would take the position that this Section owe its constitution of validity to the Fourteenth Amendment rather than the Thirteenth.","start":119.822,"stop":148.587,"duration":28.76},{"text":"And as I recall, Counsel for the petitioners and I'm sure there was no intention or whatsoever on his part to put the respondent in an incorrect position or mislead the Court.","start":148.587,"stop":161.38,"duration":12.79},{"text":"Counsel for the petitioners said, yes, he would presume that our position would be, that this Section owes its life, owes its constitutional life, you might say to the Fourteenth rather than the Thirteenth Amendment.","start":161.38,"stop":176.935,"duration":15.56},{"text":"It seems therefore that the repetition on the emphasis with which I thought, I had made it clear in my brief that we were not concerned with the constitutionality of this Section.","start":176.935,"stop":190.075,"duration":13.14},{"text":"That therefore it mattered not to us whether it should be regarded as rooted in the Thirteenth Amendment or the Fourteenth Amendment, escaped the attention of counsel for the petitioners.","start":190.075,"stop":203.984,"duration":13.91},{"text":"But, as Your Honors will recall in connection with another question counsel for the petitioners did say that we had conceded the constitutionality of this Civil Rights Act which is true.","start":203.984,"stop":218.672,"duration":14.69},{"text":"And it's for that reason that in our brief, we open up by saying that one of the three questions which the petitioners present as questions presented in this case maybe eliminated.","start":218.672,"stop":232.703,"duration":14.03},{"text":"And that question in the petitioner's brief was whether the -- whether Section 1982 is constitutional.","start":232.703,"stop":240.56,"duration":7.86},{"text":"We are not questioning the constitutionality of that Section.","start":240.56,"stop":243.852,"duration":3.29},{"text":"What are we questioning then?","start":243.852,"stop":245.83,"duration":1.98},{"text":"We're questioning the meaning of that Section.","start":245.83,"stop":248.561,"duration":2.73},{"text":"It is no matter of congressional power.","start":248.561,"stop":251.478,"duration":2.92},{"text":"But at the end of the Thirteenth or the Fourteenth or any other provision of the constitution, it isn't a question of whether had Congress in 1866 passed an Act which was directed against individual conduct whether Congress thereby was exercising a valid power either under the Thirteenth or the Fourteenth Amendment.","start":251.478,"stop":273.252,"duration":21.77},{"text":"That incidentally maybe a question that will be raised if Congress should pass a fair Housing Bill, of course, because under your customary fair housing bill, it's the individual owner or seller who is prohibited from discriminating of that may raise a question as to whether under Section 5 of the Fourteenth Amendment the enabling Section or Section 2 of the Thirteenth Amendment.","start":273.252,"stop":299.579,"duration":26.33},{"text":"Congress has the power to enact legislation of this kind.","start":299.579,"stop":304.549,"duration":4.97},{"text":"That is not the question here.","start":304.549,"stop":306.035,"duration":1.49},{"text":"So, I come to what I think is the crucial question.","start":306.035,"stop":311.887,"duration":5.85},{"text":"With respect to this statute that has been made so mush of that the honorable Attorney General relied so heavily on yesterday.","start":311.887,"stop":323.069,"duration":11.18},{"text":"This statute has some very simple words, I think.","start":323.069,"stop":328.561,"duration":5.49},{"text":"It's a question what those words mean.","start":328.561,"stop":330.092,"duration":1.53},{"text":"And if you kept down to what I think are the key words, what are they?","start":330.092,"stop":335.286,"duration":5.19},{"text":"It says, “Every person shall have the same right to buy property as is enjoyed by white citizens”.","start":335.286,"stop":348.818,"duration":13.53},{"text":"What does that mean?","start":348.818,"stop":350.737,"duration":1.92},{"text":"What does the word “right” in that sentence mean?","start":350.737,"stop":353.16,"duration":2.42},{"text":"Does it mean right in the sense of legal ability, legal competence to buy, own, and incidentally inherit?","start":353.16,"stop":362.942,"duration":9.78},{"text":"That word is also used in the statute; property and self property.","start":362.942,"stop":368.158,"duration":5.22},{"text":"Or does it mean something more than that?","start":368.158,"stop":372.201,"duration":4.04},{"text":"Doesn't mean something that is not so much related to the status of the -- or the position of the buyer as it is to the seller, to the conduct of a seller, something that is not just a matter of right but of matter of duty, a duty imposed upon the seller.","start":372.201,"stop":393.947,"duration":21.75}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you talking about 1981 --","start":393.947,"stop":395.877,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"1982 Your Honor.","start":395.877,"stop":397.866,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"1982?","start":397.866,"stop":398.6,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"1982 which is the Section involved here or 1978 of the revised statutes.","start":398.6,"stop":405.184,"duration":6.58},{"text":"That is a portion by the way, a portion of the original Civil Rights Act.","start":405.184,"stop":410.213,"duration":5.03},{"text":"You'll find that portion in the first Section of the original Act which had a number of Sections in it.","start":410.213,"stop":416.998,"duration":6.78},{"text":"Well now the petitioners in this case claimed that this Section is directed and was intended to be directed against the seller.","start":416.998,"stop":431.064,"duration":14.07},{"text":"That it didn't simply mean right in the sense of right by law legal competence.","start":431.064,"stop":438.273,"duration":7.21},{"text":"And in order to prove -- we of course take the position that this Section should be construed as being in confined to laws or official action of some kind which say that a Negro shall not have the same right as a white citizen.","start":438.273,"stop":456.604,"duration":18.33},{"text":"And it was -- it cannot be and should not be construed as being aimed, that individual, the individual behavior of a seller.","start":456.604,"stop":465.255,"duration":8.65},{"text":"Now in order to prove that its construction is correct, the petitioners and the writers of the NCADH brief, NCADH brief and that particularly the Government, I say particularly the Government for a reason which I'll mention shortly, insist on taking us back to the year 1866, to the early part of the year 1866, on the 39th Congress enacted this Section.","start":465.255,"stop":499.308,"duration":34.05},{"text":"And I must say, Your Honors, that when I saw in the Government's brief, the historical materials, the -- not secondary but primary source materials on which apparently the Government claimed its construction would be justified.","start":499.308,"stop":521.267,"duration":21.96},{"text":"I shuddered a little bit because it meant that I would have to indulge in some historical research.","start":521.267,"stop":530.626,"duration":9.36},{"text":"And I do not profess to be expert in delving into historical materials but I felt that as a lawyer, and especially since the Government gave me the specific leads, it blueprinted these sources specifically the materials which it said would prove that that was the intention of Congress in 1866, and so I went to these sources.","start":530.626,"stop":557.514,"duration":26.89},{"text":"Now, what were they?","start":557.514,"stop":559.607,"duration":2.09},{"text":"Now, I'll make this as brief as possible.","start":559.607,"stop":562.698,"duration":3.09},{"text":"The Government claims that if you consult the statements, the speeches made in Congress, the 39th Congress, the speeches of the sponsors of this Section -- of this Act of 1866, the speeches of the opponents of the Act, and one other statement, the statement of President Andrew Johnson, when he vetoed this bill, the reasons that he gave for vetoing the bill.","start":562.698,"stop":594.355,"duration":31.66},{"text":"You will find says the Government that the bill must have been intended to be directed against individual action.","start":594.355,"stop":601.169,"duration":6.81},{"text":"I must say since I mentioned President Johnson's veto message in order that the Court may follow me in connection with another matter which I shall presently mention, a very important matter which does involved a matter of comparing dates.","start":601.169,"stop":616.761,"duration":15.59},{"text":"This Act of 1866 was first enacted on March 13, 1866.","start":616.761,"stop":623.901,"duration":7.14},{"text":"President Johnson vetoed.","start":623.901,"stop":626.544,"duration":2.64},{"text":"It was then reenacted over the President's veto on April 9, which is a date usually given as a date of enactment of this Act of 1866.","start":626.544,"stop":637.693,"duration":11.15},{"text":"Now, I went into the statements, the speeches made in the congressional record.","start":637.693,"stop":644.744,"duration":7.05},{"text":"The references are all given in the Government's brief.","start":644.744,"stop":648.394,"duration":3.65},{"text":"It was not known by the way as a congressional record that -- yes, they seemed congressional globe.","start":648.394,"stop":653.823,"duration":5.43},{"text":"And I took the statements of the chairman of the judiciary committee of the House of the Senate.","start":653.823,"stop":663.124,"duration":9.3},{"text":"And I took the statements, the speeches; I read them all, of the sponsors of the bill, the people who supported the bills in both bodies of Congress.","start":663.124,"stop":673.968,"duration":10.84},{"text":"I then went to the opponents of the bill and I got their statements.","start":673.968,"stop":677.906,"duration":3.94},{"text":"And I have set forth in my brief, department passages from the statements of all of those Congressmen.","start":677.906,"stop":686.057,"duration":8.15},{"text":"And then I went to President Johnson's veto message.","start":686.057,"stop":689.431,"duration":3.37},{"text":"And I have set forth in my brief the pertinent passage from his message.","start":689.431,"stop":695.065,"duration":5.63},{"text":"All of which I submit Your Honors overwhelmingly, convincingly, proved that the bill was never intended.","start":695.065,"stop":706.447,"duration":11.38},{"text":"This Civil Rights Act of 1866 was never intended to be directed at anything but laws, legislation.","start":706.447,"stop":714.189,"duration":7.74},{"text":"And then I went to the other sources, the second source that the Government set, the second document on which it said it would be -- could be shown that this bill was intended not to be directed against discriminatory laws but individual conduct and what was that?","start":714.189,"stop":730.641,"duration":16.45},{"text":"Now, this is quite interesting.","start":730.641,"stop":733.091,"duration":2.45},{"text":"The Government says that there are two documents, a Senate executive document and a House executive document, which will prove that in all of the Black codes that were enacted after the Civil War, some of them maybe before.","start":733.091,"stop":755.704,"duration":22.61},{"text":"By the time Congress got to deliberating on this Act, all disqualification of Negroes to own property had been removed.","start":755.704,"stop":765.912,"duration":10.21},{"text":"Now, this is quite a statement.","start":765.912,"stop":767.218,"duration":1.31},{"text":"It's in the Government's brief.","start":767.218,"stop":768.27,"duration":1.05},{"text":"I think it reads -- it appears that in none of the Black codes in the early part of 1966 was there any disqualification left to the Negro from owning property?","start":768.27,"stop":779.217,"duration":10.95},{"text":"I then went to these two documents and what were they?","start":779.217,"stop":783.489,"duration":4.27},{"text":"Both of these documents contained, each contains a report.","start":783.489,"stop":787.645,"duration":4.16},{"text":"A report prepared by the then Secretary of State Mr. Stewart under the direction of President Johnson for submission to Congress.","start":787.645,"stop":795.395,"duration":7.75},{"text":"So that Congress would know what was going on so far as discriminatory legislation was concerned, discriminatory as against the Negro of course.","start":795.395,"stop":962.419,"duration":167.02},{"text":"And what does the report say?","start":962.419,"stop":807.181,"duration":-155.24},{"text":"I must say I was dismayed of what I found in the light of what the Government asserts.","start":807.181,"stop":812.563,"duration":5.38},{"text":"I found that according to that report which incidentally Your Honors adheres where that date becomes important in connection with the date of the passage of this bill.","start":812.563,"stop":821.129,"duration":8.57},{"text":"This report is dated May 22, 1966, which was after the originally enactment of the bill as well as its reenactment following President Johnson's veto.","start":821.129,"stop":836.892,"duration":15.76},{"text":"It says that in all -- it let -- it reviews a number of the Southern States.","start":836.892,"stop":842.904,"duration":6.01},{"text":"And it says that in all of those states with two exceptions, the disqualifications of the Negroes still remain.","start":842.904,"stop":850.844,"duration":7.94},{"text":"It points it out very clearly and I will presently show how.","start":850.844,"stop":855.68,"duration":4.84},{"text":"Apparently, what happened was and in each of these states, a state convention was called, as this is of course familiar Post Civil War history.","start":855.68,"stop":864.41,"duration":8.73},{"text":"A state convention was called by the provincial Governor of the state appointed by President Johnson, Andrew Johnson.","start":864.41,"stop":873.491,"duration":9.08},{"text":"The convention was called and of course it was completely dominated by the Northerners and their Southern sympathizers.","start":873.491,"stop":880.814,"duration":7.32},{"text":"And so, there was no difficulty whatsoever in getting resolutions adopted that would be in line with Northern feelings.","start":880.814,"stop":887.723,"duration":6.91},{"text":"In each of these states says this report, in each of these states, first, there was a resolution adopted, proclaiming that there would be no more slavery in that state.","start":887.723,"stop":901.205,"duration":13.48},{"text":"Then it was followed in -- I think every case by another resolution.","start":901.205,"stop":905.379,"duration":4.17},{"text":"And that second resolution called upon the chairman of the convention to appoint a committee or a commission that would come in with a set of recommended laws, revisions of the then existing state laws in order to bring the state laws into conformity with the Thirteenth Amendment, with the emancipation situation.","start":905.379,"stop":928.921,"duration":23.54},{"text":"And what happened?","start":928.921,"stop":929.822,"duration":0.9},{"text":"According to this report, most of these cases such a committee was appointed.","start":929.822,"stop":937.711,"duration":7.89},{"text":"In several of the cases, several of the states, the committee actually went to work.","start":937.711,"stop":942.166,"duration":4.46},{"text":"And there is set forth in the report a set of statutes in which, of course, all disqualification of the Negro was eliminated.","start":942.166,"stop":952.45,"duration":10.28},{"text":"But this was a set of statutes which the committee, the commission, and the convention resolved, should be recommended for enactment by the local legislature.","start":952.45,"stop":964.881,"duration":12.43},{"text":"Except in two cases, Texas and Georgia as of the date of this report, no such legislation has yet been enacted.","start":964.881,"stop":975.563,"duration":10.68},{"text":"And interestingly enough, even in Texas and Georgia which had changed their laws and had removed disqualification.","start":975.563,"stop":983.36,"duration":7.8},{"text":"When did that take place?","start":983.36,"stop":985.287,"duration":1.93},{"text":"Not before this bill was passed.","start":985.287,"stop":987.813,"duration":2.53},{"text":"In one case it took place several weeks but in both cases, it took place after the first enactment of the bill.","start":987.813,"stop":995.164,"duration":7.35},{"text":"And in one case, it took place before its reenactment but certainly after the originally enactment of this bill.","start":995.164,"stop":1002.775,"duration":7.61},{"text":"For the Government therefore to say that when Congress was debating, considering this bill, there was no need to do anything about discriminatory laws from these black codes to me is astonishing.","start":1002.775,"stop":1016.259,"duration":13.48},{"text":"It's contradicted by the evidence I submit.","start":1016.259,"stop":1018.871,"duration":2.61},{"text":"And furthermore, Your Honors, if you want what I say in my brief, it's probably the best succinct piece of evidence on that point that you would want.","start":1018.871,"stop":1029.66,"duration":10.79},{"text":"It's that of Justice Wayne who in that very year was deciding the case sitting as a Circuit Justice.","start":1029.66,"stop":1036.925,"duration":7.26},{"text":"He was deciding the case of U.S. versus Rhodes.","start":1036.925,"stop":1040.078,"duration":3.15},{"text":"And in the course of his opinion, he makes the statement, I quote it in my brief, that as soon as the Thirteenth Amendment was passed, there begun a course of legislative oppression, legislative oppression through this Black codes of course.","start":1040.078,"stop":1057.394,"duration":17.32},{"text":"And that this statute obviously, I don't know whether to use the word “obviously or undoubtedly”, was enacted to curve that course of legislative oppression.","start":1057.394,"stop":1069.886,"duration":12.49},{"text":"There you have the real purpose of the statute.","start":1069.886,"stop":1073.081,"duration":3.19},{"text":"Law, discriminatory law is not an individual conduct.","start":1073.081,"stop":1077.451,"duration":4.37},{"text":"Now, passing from the context, the setting in which the Act was enacted, I'm looking at what's happened to this Act.","start":1077.451,"stop":1087.794,"duration":10.34},{"text":"After all it's over a hundred years, this Act has been existence.","start":1087.794,"stop":1091.996,"duration":4.2},{"text":"The natural question is, why hasn't it been used before in a situation of this kind?","start":1091.996,"stop":1097.119,"duration":5.12},{"text":"Why hasn't it used before in a situation where a discriminatory law was not involved but discriminatory conduct?","start":1097.119,"stop":1111.33,"duration":14.21}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Trieman, what did the sponsors of the bill say on the floor of Congress --","start":1111.33,"stop":1117.525,"duration":6.2}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Set forth in my brief, Your Honor the --","start":1117.525,"stop":1119.07,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right (Voice Overlap) --","start":1119.07,"stop":1119.602,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you like for me to read it?","start":1119.602,"stop":1120.746,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"True but --","start":1120.746,"stop":1123.519,"duration":2.77}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"They --","start":1123.519,"stop":1124.715,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- did they assert anything on this particular issue that you're talking about now?","start":1124.715,"stop":1128.028,"duration":3.31}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Specifically --","start":1128.028,"stop":1129.498,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon?","start":1129.498,"stop":1129.889,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Specifically, in fact --","start":1129.889,"stop":1131.009,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What?","start":1131.009,"stop":1131.229,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the times they were asked.","start":1131.229,"stop":1132.533,"duration":1.3},{"text":"Are you intending to go into our states and make a criminal code directed against individuals and the answer was no, not at all.","start":1132.533,"stop":1139.177,"duration":6.64},{"text":"In those states where your laws do not disqualify this statute will have no effect.","start":1139.177,"stop":1145.539,"duration":6.36},{"text":"Specifically, they say that.","start":1145.539,"stop":1147.912,"duration":2.37},{"text":"And I have the quotations in my brief.","start":1147.912,"stop":1149.86,"duration":1.95},{"text":"And I have those particular passages in bold type about eight -10 pages of it.","start":1149.86,"stop":1158.263,"duration":8.4}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is that an answer to this -- to what the Government contends here?","start":1158.263,"stop":1163.097,"duration":4.83}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes.","start":1163.097,"stop":1163.738,"duration":0.64},{"text":"The Government says that --","start":1163.738,"stop":1164.795,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"This is -- this doesn't say anything a criminal statute?","start":1164.795,"stop":1170.651,"duration":5.86}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but the point is that --","start":1170.651,"stop":1171.956,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"This says they have the right to --","start":1171.956,"stop":1174.037,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"To have what?","start":1174.037,"stop":1174.797,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"To -- they -- this says they have the right to buy or to lease and so forth.","start":1174.797,"stop":1178.614,"duration":3.82}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":1178.614,"stop":1180.949,"duration":2.34},{"text":"And as I see it, Mr. Chief Justice, the Government says, well, that word “right” means -- I think that is Mr. Liberman said yesterday has to do with the extension which you can enjoy the right.","start":1180.949,"stop":1192.937,"duration":11.99},{"text":"It isn't only a matter of legal right of right by law.","start":1192.937,"stop":1196.691,"duration":3.75},{"text":"It's a matter of whether you can get somebody else, an unwilling seller whether you can compel him to sell to you because he is willing to sell it to somebody else who is not a Negro.","start":1196.691,"stop":1207.293,"duration":10.6},{"text":"So it's a question of whether this statute is directed against laws only --","start":1207.293,"stop":1212.84,"duration":5.55}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes I understand that.","start":1212.84,"stop":1214.224,"duration":1.38},{"text":"But is there any specific language that you can point to by the sponsors of the bill which says this is not directed against the individual but is directed against the states?","start":1214.224,"stop":1226.689,"duration":12.47}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I think so Your Honor, and I have this passages --","start":1226.689,"stop":1228.383,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, could you point it out --","start":1228.383,"stop":1229.426,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes.","start":1229.426,"stop":1229.582,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"-- to me in your brief?","start":1229.582,"stop":1230.053,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll see if I can get it immediately.","start":1230.053,"stop":1236.414,"duration":6.36}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Page 14 in your brief?","start":1236.414,"stop":1237.849,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":1237.849,"stop":1238.805,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Page 14 of your brief?","start":1238.805,"stop":1242.605,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1242.605,"stop":1247.01,"duration":4.4}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"14?","start":1247.01,"stop":1247.912,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, the part in bold type.","start":1247.912,"stop":1252.074,"duration":4.16},{"text":"In an -- if an offense is committed against a colored person simply because he is colored in a state where the law affords him the same protection as if he were white, this Act neither has no -- or was intended to have anything to do with this case.","start":1252.074,"stop":1268.32,"duration":16.25}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, was that addressed to this specific Section as to 1982 or to other parts of the bill than before the Congress?","start":1268.32,"stop":1276.822,"duration":8.5}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I didn't get your question Mr. Justice.","start":1276.822,"stop":1278.698,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Was that remark addressed to this specific Section which we now call 1982 --","start":1278.698,"stop":1284.033,"duration":5.33}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"It wasn't (Voice Overlap) --","start":1284.033,"stop":1284.277,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- or was it addressed to the statute as a whole -- bill as whole or to other parts of it?","start":1284.277,"stop":1293.479,"duration":9.2},{"text":"I know for example that there's a reference in the preceding sentence that you have quoted in your brief to the words under color of law.","start":1293.479,"stop":1303.843,"duration":10.36}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1303.843,"stop":1304.873,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, those words don't appear, do they in 1982?","start":1304.873,"stop":1310.446,"duration":5.57}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"That question is not easy to answer, Mr. Justice Fortas because --","start":1310.446,"stop":1313.604,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it maybe a critical question because the legislative material that you are using in your brief may apply to 1982 or may apply to other provisions of the bill.","start":1313.604,"stop":1327.808,"duration":14.2},{"text":"That's what makes this inquiry so difficult --","start":1327.808,"stop":1330.813,"duration":3.01}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree.","start":1330.813,"stop":1330.882,"duration":0.07}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and so confusing.","start":1330.882,"stop":1332.051,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree, I cannot say confidently that the Congressman who made that statement had in mind only that portion of it which is today 1982 or other portions.","start":1332.051,"stop":1341.309,"duration":9.26},{"text":"And I'm well aware Mr. Justice Fortas that the phrase under color of law appears in another part of the Act, yes.","start":1341.309,"stop":1349.549,"duration":8.24}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any other language on the part of the sponsors that you rely on?","start":1349.549,"stop":1361.678,"duration":12.13}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"On page 15.","start":1361.678,"stop":1364.753,"duration":3.07},{"text":"In the statement of Representative Wilson, if the states would all observe the rights of our citizens, there would be no need of this bill.","start":1364.753,"stop":1372.213,"duration":7.46},{"text":"And then later on he speaks of laws barbaric, nothing said about individual conduct.","start":1372.213,"stop":1379.411,"duration":7.2}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, again he's talking about the whole bill, aren't they?","start":1379.411,"stop":1383.514,"duration":4.1}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe he was but after all, that bill included this Section.","start":1383.514,"stop":1394.151,"duration":10.64}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it your argument that the law would apply to Missouri if Missouri had laws -- discrimination but that since Missouri has no laws in discriminating, it does not apply in Missouri, is that your argument?","start":1394.151,"stop":1417.663,"duration":23.51}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"In effect I suppose it would be so far as this Section is concerned.","start":1417.663,"stop":1421.933,"duration":4.27},{"text":"Now that -- not under the Fourteenth Amendment --","start":1421.933,"stop":1424.235,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That the --","start":1424.235,"stop":1424.629,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1424.629,"stop":1425.078,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Operation of the law depends then upon what -- what are the laws of the state.","start":1425.078,"stop":1429.013,"duration":3.93}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Laws, ordinances, official regulations, official conduct, yes.","start":1429.013,"stop":1433.782,"duration":4.77}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"This would seem to indicate to the minds of some, they had an idea that would apply to those states that had so-called Black Codes, but did not apply to any other state?","start":1433.782,"stop":1448.038,"duration":14.26}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Black Codes --","start":1448.038,"stop":1449,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that what you're arguing?","start":1449,"stop":1450.391,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Black Codes that had disqualifications and some of the Black Codes did not, yes, yes.","start":1450.391,"stop":1455.213,"duration":4.82},{"text":"In fact I think that's --","start":1455.213,"stop":1456.079,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"So that the law would change, federal law would change according to the -- what the law in the paper?","start":1456.079,"stop":1465.907,"duration":9.83}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would say that an action under that law would not be possible in a state that has no discriminatory laws, yes.","start":1465.907,"stop":1476.112,"duration":10.21},{"text":"That's it precisely.","start":1476.112,"stop":1476.685,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"An action under it but it refers to rights?","start":1476.685,"stop":1479.957,"duration":3.27}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes?","start":1479.957,"stop":1481.438,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is that in (Voice Overlap) --","start":1481.438,"stop":1482.156,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"In the sense of a law.","start":1482.156,"stop":1483.474,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that inapplicable to a state that does not have such laws?","start":1483.474,"stop":1488.106,"duration":4.63}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I would think if there are no laws, no regulations, there would be no action under this, under this particular --","start":1488.106,"stop":1495.068,"duration":6.96}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"There'd be no action but -- because there'd be no need for action perhaps?","start":1495.068,"stop":1500.524,"duration":5.46}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"(Inaudible)","start":1500.524,"stop":1501.298,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But --","start":1501.298,"stop":1501.96,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there are --","start":1501.96,"stop":1503.436,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Does that change the language which says they shall have their right, somebody shall have their right -- a citizen shall have the right?","start":1503.436,"stop":1515.901,"duration":12.47}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Does it change the language?","start":1515.901,"stop":1517.724,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, does it make that ineffective for a state to -- if it have laws which do provide protection?","start":1517.724,"stop":1530.251,"duration":12.53}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"But where the protection is not actually enforced because some individuals choose to be discriminatory.","start":1530.251,"stop":1536.449,"duration":6.2}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1536.449,"stop":1536.639,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that what you mean?","start":1536.639,"stop":1537.393,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"No, that's part of it?","start":1537.393,"stop":1538.508,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1538.508,"stop":1539.088,"duration":0.58},{"text":"Well, I would say that's right.","start":1539.088,"stop":1540.203,"duration":1.12},{"text":"I would say he'd have to go elsewhere for his remedy but not under this Section.","start":1540.203,"stop":1544.068,"duration":3.87}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Section would become inoperative then.","start":1544.068,"stop":1547.413,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a proclamation of rights, Your Honor, as many scholars have pointed out --","start":1547.413,"stop":1551.509,"duration":4.1}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it's a proclamation of right which is a legal right, isn't it?","start":1551.509,"stop":1554.328,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, yes.","start":1554.328,"stop":1555.941,"duration":1.61},{"text":"Like some -- like the Fourteenth Amendment --","start":1555.941,"stop":1556.513,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Somebody has rights and who is this somebody?","start":1556.513,"stop":1560.564,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I believe that the answer to that is the same that should be given and I'd intend to give when I discussed the Fourteenth Amendment in its bare terms.","start":1560.564,"stop":1568.075,"duration":7.51}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, what does this statute say?","start":1568.075,"stop":1570.687,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"It merely says --","start":1570.687,"stop":1571.203,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Who has that right?","start":1571.203,"stop":1575.114,"duration":3.91}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"It merely says that there is a right not to have a law.","start":1575.114,"stop":1580.969,"duration":5.86}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It says all the citizens of the United States shall have the same right and who's they're talking about?","start":1580.969,"stop":1589.828,"duration":8.86},{"text":"Is that talking about a state or citizens of a state?","start":1589.828,"stop":1593.169,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say that the right there and I don't deny, Mr. Justice Black.","start":1593.169,"stop":1598.028,"duration":4.86},{"text":"We do get into a realm here that to some extent may depend upon semantics upon the objective one has in mind in trying to interpret this Section.","start":1598.028,"stop":1608.265,"duration":10.24},{"text":"I can only go by what the Congressman said back on those days by what President Johnson said in his veto message when he said that in his opinion this would change the laws of the states.","start":1608.265,"stop":1622.767,"duration":14.5},{"text":"And he didn't want Congress to meddle with local laws.","start":1622.767,"stop":1626.914,"duration":4.15},{"text":"And I would say the same thing same conclusion must be reached in reading Justice Wayne's opinion.","start":1626.914,"stop":1631.865,"duration":4.95}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, wasn't this evidently intended to change the law of the state?","start":1631.865,"stop":1636.757,"duration":4.89},{"text":"Wasn't that the very purpose of the statute?","start":1636.757,"stop":1638.626,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I agree, of course in those states where they have discriminatory laws.","start":1638.626,"stop":1643.096,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But I find that -- here's my trouble with your argument up to this time.","start":1643.096,"stop":1647.536,"duration":4.44},{"text":"I find nothing to indicate that this right which was intended to be concurred upon the circumstance was automatically withdrawn on the passage of a law by the state just take care of that same thing.","start":1647.536,"stop":1659.87,"duration":12.33}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not so sure I would say it would be automatically rid -- gone, it's there hovering all the time in the moment the state does pass a law.","start":1659.87,"stop":1666.652,"duration":6.78},{"text":"This is discriminatory.","start":1666.652,"stop":1667.823,"duration":1.17},{"text":"That Section could be invoked.","start":1667.823,"stop":1669.515,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"A federal law which is effective only if the state doesn't have a law of the same kind.","start":1669.515,"stop":1673.21,"duration":3.69}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Only if the state passes a law in violation of that Section and I might at this point, Your Honor, perhaps call your attention to this statement in --","start":1673.21,"stop":1682.835,"duration":9.63}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"In Missouri, could a group organize this association or corporation under state law, get a permit to bill the segregated housing project?","start":1682.835,"stop":1699.793,"duration":16.96}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"That would depend on who the group is --","start":1699.793,"stop":1702.046,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the group --","start":1702.046,"stop":1702.097,"duration":0.05}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"If the group is in any way financed by any kind of state agency --","start":1702.097,"stop":1704.902,"duration":2.81}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Unless, they go to the corporation counsel to get a permit to build and construct the segregated housing facilities, would that be possible?","start":1704.902,"stop":1712.782,"duration":7.88}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"If they go to the commission, the plan commission to get approval of their subdivision plan?","start":1712.782,"stop":1716.946,"duration":4.16}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, no, the corporation commission they want to cooperate in order to bill segregated housing project.","start":1716.946,"stop":1723.854,"duration":6.91},{"text":"Could they be incorporated for that purpose?","start":1723.854,"stop":1726.64,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"You mean in the corporate purposes, it would be set forth that they were going to have (Voice Overlap) --","start":1726.64,"stop":1729.857,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the purpose.","start":1729.857,"stop":1730.962,"duration":1.11},{"text":"Yes.","start":1730.962,"stop":1731.256,"duration":0.29},{"text":"The purpose is to bill segregated housing (Voice Overlap) --","start":1731.256,"stop":1733.395,"duration":2.14}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"This would depend on the attitude of the Secretary of State when he reads the proposed articles of (Voice Overlap) --","start":1733.395,"stop":1737.781,"duration":4.39}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Alright, he reads it and then he issues a certificate, would that be -- are you then in the middle of a constitutional (Voice Overlap) --","start":1737.781,"stop":1744.43,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say I think you're getting pretty close to Shelly versus Kraemer.","start":1744.43,"stop":1748.71,"duration":4.28},{"text":"You're getting pretty close to action by an official.","start":1748.71,"stop":1751.841,"duration":3.13},{"text":"If he approves Articles within the corporation that explicitly state that this will be segregated, yes.","start":1751.841,"stop":1758.549,"duration":6.71},{"text":"I would say this is official conduct.","start":1758.549,"stop":1761.355,"duration":2.81},{"text":"It's giving the sanction of the state to something that's clearly unconstitutional, yes I would.","start":1761.355,"stop":1767.429,"duration":6.07}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you agree that this area could qualify as a city of the fourth class?","start":1767.429,"stop":1775.082,"duration":7.65}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"On the basis of population, I suppose it would.","start":1775.082,"stop":1779.863,"duration":4.78},{"text":"Any group of individuals in a certain area under our state statutes, now I presume this is true all over.","start":1779.863,"stop":1787.093,"duration":7.23},{"text":"If they have a certain number of people can qualify for a certain type of incorporate --","start":1787.093,"stop":1791.754,"duration":4.66}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, assuming they did.","start":1791.754,"stop":1794.586,"duration":2.83}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"They incorporated --","start":1794.586,"stop":1795.644,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"As of (Voice Overlap) --","start":1795.644,"stop":1796.229,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"And it was a (Voice Overlap) --","start":1796.229,"stop":1796.438,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Setting the fourth class and pass an ordinance which prohibited all Negroes and cats who live in there?","start":1796.438,"stop":1804.738,"duration":8.3}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say --","start":1804.738,"stop":1805.821,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that a private action?","start":1805.821,"stop":1807.561,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Marshall, that to me would be as violative as anything could possibly be because there you're getting with a political subdivision.","start":1807.561,"stop":1812.77,"duration":5.21}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"What?","start":1812.77,"stop":1813.17,"duration":0.4},{"text":"What would it violate, the Fourteenth Amendment?","start":1813.17,"stop":1815.282,"duration":2.11}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Would violate the Fourteenth Amendment.","start":1815.282,"stop":1817.126,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what's the difference between this situation and the formality of the clan in a city?","start":1817.126,"stop":1824.169,"duration":7.04}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I can answer that --","start":1824.169,"stop":1824.6,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"What would the city of the -- what would the city of the fourth class have to this area does not have?","start":1824.6,"stop":1830.596,"duration":6}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"The city of the fourth class would be a political subdivision of the state.","start":1830.596,"stop":1835.796,"duration":5.2}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And that's the only difference?","start":1835.796,"stop":1838.187,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a very important difference I think, Mr. Justice Marshall, for this reason.","start":1838.187,"stop":1841.164,"duration":2.98},{"text":"The City of Saint Louis for example, could not in selling any part of its property discriminate --","start":1841.164,"stop":1849.774,"duration":8.61}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but any --","start":1849.774,"stop":1849.937,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"But a private owner --","start":1849.937,"stop":1851.181,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"No, could any other city in Missouri?","start":1851.181,"stop":1853.163,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, but a private owner and you yesterday mentioned --","start":1853.163,"stop":1856.844,"duration":3.68}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Even though the private owner has a piece of property as large as a city of the fourth class with everything else that the city of the fourth class has nearly because it is “private” is out from under the Fourteenth Amendment.","start":1856.844,"stop":1876.123,"duration":19.28}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Marshall, you are now reaching the point which I think some of your question yesterday was directed to and that involves the case Marsh versus Alabama.","start":1876.123,"stop":1884.699,"duration":8.58},{"text":"And I am most anxious to discuss that case.","start":1884.699,"stop":1887.381,"duration":2.68},{"text":"I had deferred it because as I've said earlier, I want to deal with these questions under two categories and your question, I --","start":1887.381,"stop":1893.604,"duration":6.22}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, whenever you're ready I'll be here.","start":1893.604,"stop":1895.575,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I'll -- no, I -- I think I would just assume Mr. Justice Marshall since you are interested in that point and it's a tremendously important point and I must say when I read Marsh versus Alabama for the first time in connection with this case, I said well, this is on all fours, how can we get around that case?","start":1895.575,"stop":1917.578,"duration":22},{"text":"Here is a big community, not in -- not a city, a company owned town.","start":1917.578,"stop":1924.894,"duration":7.32},{"text":"And here was the United States Supreme Court Holding that the fact that it was all privately owned didn't settle the question.","start":1924.894,"stop":1935.764,"duration":10.87},{"text":"I think that was the expression used by Mr. Justice Black in his opinion in that case.","start":1935.764,"stop":1939.836,"duration":4.07},{"text":"Property rights do not settle the question.","start":1939.836,"stop":1942.082,"duration":2.25},{"text":"Now what happened in that case?","start":1942.082,"stop":1944.053,"duration":1.97},{"text":"It was a Jehovah's Witness by a name of Marsh who came under this company owned town, I think it was suburb of Mobile, Alabama and the -- want to distribute some religious literature.","start":1944.053,"stop":1956.661,"duration":12.61},{"text":"And the company representatives told her, there was a regulation against it, warned her to -- not to do so.","start":1956.661,"stop":1963.36,"duration":6.7},{"text":"Despite the warning, she continued to sell the literature.","start":1963.36,"stop":1966.511,"duration":3.15},{"text":"She was arrested on a charged of violating the local in effect trespass statute.","start":1966.511,"stop":1973.297,"duration":6.79},{"text":"She was convicted.","start":1973.297,"stop":1974.617,"duration":1.32},{"text":"She took an appeal to this Court.","start":1974.617,"stop":1976.725,"duration":2.11},{"text":"This Court held that she was protected by the constitutional provision.","start":1976.725,"stop":1980.496,"duration":3.77},{"text":"This happened to be the First Amendment, but the same point of course would apply that was within constitutional prohibition.","start":1980.496,"stop":1989.81,"duration":9.31},{"text":"And you might say therefore, “Well, doesn't this control this case?”","start":1989.81,"stop":1993.56,"duration":3.75},{"text":"Not one bit for this reason.","start":1993.56,"stop":1997.063,"duration":3.5},{"text":"And I think as I pointed out in my brief, the best way to meet that case is to consider a similar case that arose two years later, the Watchtower case also involving Jehovah's Witnesses.","start":1997.063,"stop":2013.283,"duration":16.22},{"text":"Now what was the Watchtower?","start":2013.283,"stop":2014.374,"duration":1.09},{"text":"It rose in New York.","start":2014.374,"stop":2017.27,"duration":2.9},{"text":"It came however as I should presently point out to the Supreme Court on request for certiorari.","start":2017.27,"stop":2022.919,"duration":5.65},{"text":"Mr. Justice Marshall since you are interested in size, I should like to describe this residential community.","start":2022.919,"stop":2031.437,"duration":8.52},{"text":"It was involved in a Watchtower Case.","start":2031.437,"stop":2033.978,"duration":2.54},{"text":"It was called Parkchester.","start":2033.978,"stop":2037.169,"duration":3.19},{"text":"And it is described this way.","start":2037.169,"stop":2049.77,"duration":12.6},{"text":"Parkchester is a residential community which is said to be the largest of its kind in the world covering 129 acres and housing 12,000 family units made up of some 35,000 people in 171 adjoining in interrelated apartment building.","start":2049.77,"stop":2067.753,"duration":17.98},{"text":"And then he was on to say that it has streets, and shops, and it's a regular community, but all privately owned.","start":2067.753,"stop":2075.121,"duration":7.37},{"text":"And the Jehovah's Witnesses came there, entered one of these apartment buildings and then in the hallways tried to distribute that literature.","start":2075.121,"stop":2081.094,"duration":5.97},{"text":"Their attention was called to the fact that there was a regulation there by the landlord, the owner of this community.","start":2081.094,"stop":2086.163,"duration":5.07},{"text":"No distribution of literature in the hallways of any department.","start":2086.163,"stop":2089.668,"duration":3.51},{"text":"Where they're apparently relying on Marsh versus Alabama refused to abide instead of getting themselves arrested as I recall they challenged the validity of that regulation in the New York Courts, the New York Court of Appeals --","start":2089.668,"stop":2101.643,"duration":11.97}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I do see a difference between an apartment house and this --","start":2101.643,"stop":2105.731,"duration":4.09}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Between the hallway?","start":2105.731,"stop":2106.993,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of an apartment house and the area we're talking about here.","start":2106.993,"stop":2112.595,"duration":5.6}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, not inside the apartments, I'm talking about the hallways.","start":2112.595,"stop":2116.459,"duration":3.86}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I say -- I see a difference between a hallway of an apartment house and this area.","start":2116.459,"stop":2124.165,"duration":7.71}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, may I then read to you --","start":2124.165,"stop":2126.784,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"The petitioner here is not encroached on anybody's property.","start":2126.784,"stop":2132.555,"duration":5.77},{"text":"He's trying to buy a house.","start":2132.555,"stop":2134.921,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"But --","start":2134.921,"stop":2135.196,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"On the city of the fourth class says, \"You can't buy it\".","start":2135.196,"stop":2138.761,"duration":3.57},{"text":"The only difference is they just didn't go to the formality of qualifying as a city of the fourth class.","start":2138.761,"stop":2146.605,"duration":7.84}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"The difference I think Mr. Justice Marshall is this.","start":2146.605,"stop":2149.755,"duration":3.15},{"text":"What part of this subdivision that we're talking about?","start":2149.755,"stop":2153.818,"duration":4.06},{"text":"If you're talking about the lot in the home that the Jones' here wanted to buy that in a language of Mr. Justice Black in Marsh versus Alabama was never intended to be open for general public used.","start":2153.818,"stop":2164.967,"duration":11.15}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"All I'm talking about --","start":2164.967,"stop":2165.221,"duration":0.25}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"This is --","start":2165.221,"stop":2166.457,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"-- is just to whether or not the fact that this area involved here was never made a city of the fourth class, that solely because of that.","start":2166.457,"stop":2179.695,"duration":13.24},{"text":"It escapes all responsibility under the Fourteenth Amendment.","start":2179.695,"stop":2183.64,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Not all responsibility.","start":2183.64,"stop":2185.558,"duration":1.92},{"text":"Not its public, not those areas, the sidewalks, the streets, the parks that are opened up for public use.","start":2185.558,"stop":2192.638,"duration":7.08},{"text":"And again using the words --","start":2192.638,"stop":2192.651,"duration":0.01}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, could they be closed?","start":2192.651,"stop":2194.467,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":2194.467,"stop":2194.944,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Couldn't they be closed?","start":2194.944,"stop":2197.406,"duration":2.46}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Not the streets, not -- yes, they could be closed completely for certain purposes but not under a discriminatory basis.","start":2197.406,"stop":2204.252,"duration":6.85}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"But they could be closed completely?","start":2204.252,"stop":2206.369,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"To Ne -- to white people as well as Negroes if they're private streets, certainly.","start":2206.369,"stop":2210.124,"duration":3.75}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, are they private streets or not?","start":2210.124,"stop":2211.326,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Some are private, yes and I'm glad you asked that question.","start":2211.326,"stop":2214,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Are some public?","start":2214,"stop":2215.169,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, yes, some are private and some are public.","start":2215.169,"stop":2217.133,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, how would I know when I'm on a private ground, when I'm on a public ground in this area?","start":2217.133,"stop":2221.009,"duration":3.88}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Sometimes you don't.","start":2221.009,"stop":2222.421,"duration":1.41},{"text":"Into my own subdivision for example --","start":2222.421,"stop":2223.721,"duration":1.3}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"And I take a chance on going to jail for trespass?","start":2223.721,"stop":2227.062,"duration":3.34}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, not necessarily, they have this wooden horse that at one end they close him up at one end, I'm sure the same is true, all of the county in order to keep him from becoming appropriated by the public and keep it private.","start":2227.062,"stop":2238.098,"duration":11.04},{"text":"All that privacy means really in those cases is -- a subdivision has to maintain them.","start":2238.098,"stop":2242.607,"duration":4.51},{"text":"They would love to dedicate some of these private streets and get the county or the state to take over the maintenance.","start":2242.607,"stop":2249.765,"duration":7.16}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- maybe I cut you off but just now, what is the difference between this and Marsh?","start":2249.765,"stop":2257.936,"duration":8.17}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I concede the difference is as to what is involved here, I mean what the discrimination is supposed to affect.","start":2257.936,"stop":2267.736,"duration":9.8},{"text":"In this case, it's supposed to affect a private lot, walks, an area that was not intended for public use, I must come back to Mr. Justice Black's language in the unanimous opinion of the Court in the Marsh case --","start":2267.736,"stop":2279.07,"duration":11.33}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I have trouble with it not to be in set aside for public use.","start":2279.07,"stop":2282.549,"duration":3.48},{"text":"It was offered for sale to the public.","start":2282.549,"stop":2284.548,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Not for public use.","start":2284.548,"stop":2286.125,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Was it offered to the sale to the public?","start":2286.125,"stop":2288.171,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- was offered for sale --","start":2288.171,"stop":2290.76,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"To the public?","start":2290.76,"stop":2290.786,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Just as any private property might be offered for sale.","start":2290.786,"stop":2293.656,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"To the public?","start":2293.656,"stop":2296.282,"duration":2.63}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2296.282,"stop":2298.409,"duration":2.13},{"text":"Mr. Justice Marshall, if I were the owner --","start":2298.409,"stop":2299.491,"duration":1.08}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, do you take the position that a right to buy a property is not as higher right as a right to hand out pamphlets?","start":2299.491,"stop":2307.223,"duration":7.73}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I most certainly do.","start":2307.223,"stop":2308.13,"duration":0.91},{"text":"I think that the right to buy and sell property, property and as distinguished from its use.","start":2308.13,"stop":2314.863,"duration":6.73}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"I think you've added something, I said the right to buy a property.","start":2314.863,"stop":2317.901,"duration":3.04},{"text":"I didn't say anything about selling.","start":2317.901,"stop":2319.652,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"The right to buy a property?","start":2319.652,"stop":2320.516,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Property isn't it just as strong in the constitution as the right to pay as out pamphlets?","start":2320.516,"stop":2328.063,"duration":7.55}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I think under the existing state of the law, in the absence of legislation pursuant to either as I say to Section 5 of the Fourteenth Amendment or Section 2 of the Thirteenth, I don't know of any law at the present time that gives to the buyer the right to buy something from somebody who is unwilling to sell it to him under our existing law.","start":2328.063,"stop":2350.226,"duration":22.16}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, is there any law that gives a corporation of this size, controlling this much land, the right to -- fends out one group of people solely because of race or color?","start":2350.226,"stop":2366.051,"duration":15.82}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say that under the existing law and I would add unfortunately I'm afraid that is so, Mr. Justice Marshall, until Congress passes a fair housing law.","start":2366.051,"stop":2375.668,"duration":9.62},{"text":"And this is what disturbs me.","start":2375.668,"stop":2377.403,"duration":1.73},{"text":"Mr. Justice Fortas yesterday --","start":2377.403,"stop":2378.152,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I mean --","start":2378.152,"stop":2379.284,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":2379.284,"stop":2380.878,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"This Court could do it, couldn't they?","start":2380.878,"stop":2382.712,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":2382.712,"stop":2383.419,"duration":0.71}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"This Court could do it, couldn't they?","start":2383.419,"stop":2386.993,"duration":3.57}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, it could of course.","start":2386.993,"stop":2388.743,"duration":1.75},{"text":"And this is what shocked me a little bit yesterday when a question was asked to the Honorable Attorney General about Mr. Justice White I think.","start":2388.743,"stop":2395.709,"duration":6.97},{"text":"I think Mr. Justice White asked the Attorney General, “Well, wouldn't our decision then make unnecessary a fair housing law?”","start":2395.709,"stop":2403.604,"duration":7.89},{"text":"And the Honorable Attorney General said, “No”, he didn't think so because this decision would be broader than a fair housing law order.","start":2403.604,"stop":2411.863,"duration":8.26},{"text":"To me, the whole is greater than of -- any of its parts.","start":2411.863,"stop":2416.208,"duration":4.35},{"text":"If you go (Inaudible) as you might say why would you need?","start":2416.208,"stop":2420.807,"duration":4.6},{"text":"Why would you need a narrower type of legislation?","start":2420.807,"stop":2424.863,"duration":4.06},{"text":"It would -- would it not then -- and this -- since I started to say is what disturbs me a great deal.","start":2424.863,"stop":2430.545,"duration":5.68},{"text":"And I hope this Court will also bear this in mind.","start":2430.545,"stop":2433.517,"duration":2.97},{"text":"I was very much impressed yesterday by a reference of Mr. Justice Fortas made to align from Oscar Wilde.","start":2433.517,"stop":2439.99,"duration":6.47},{"text":"We kill that which we -- the thing we love.","start":2439.99,"stop":2444.762,"duration":4.77},{"text":"Isn't -- not possible that trying to get this Court, the federal courts to do something which so many people are asking Congress to do might in some way --","start":2444.762,"stop":2457.195,"duration":12.43}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you agree that Congress can do it?","start":2457.195,"stop":2459.218,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":2459.218,"stop":2459.97,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you agree that Congress has power to do it?","start":2459.97,"stop":2464.733,"duration":4.76}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I would rather not ask -- answer that question, Your Honor.","start":2464.733,"stop":2467.133,"duration":2.4},{"text":"It's not involved in this case.","start":2467.133,"stop":2468.29,"duration":1.16},{"text":"And I have not made a sufficient study.","start":2468.29,"stop":2470.911,"duration":2.62},{"text":"I --","start":2470.911,"stop":2471.068,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it seems to me like your argument is really a challenge to the power of Congress under the Section 5 of the Amendment.","start":2471.068,"stop":2481.634,"duration":10.57}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say if Congress does pass such a law to this, then would be the question, has Congress --","start":2481.634,"stop":2487.247,"duration":5.61}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it seems to me like that's the argument you are making on the --","start":2487.247,"stop":2490.854,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- then I've been misunderstood.","start":2490.854,"stop":2491.704,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- while you categorize it as an argument as to what the statute does.","start":2491.704,"stop":2497.349,"duration":5.64},{"text":"It seems to me what you're saying is, we've got the whole statute didn't do that because Congress didn't have that power.","start":2497.349,"stop":2504.878,"duration":7.53},{"text":"And for -- as for myself, I have said they did with reference to Section 5.","start":2504.878,"stop":2511.253,"duration":6.38}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it maybe, it maybe but I don't -- in this case involves that question because we have no legislation.","start":2511.253,"stop":2518.449,"duration":7.2},{"text":"We're dealing here with the bare terms of the Fourteenth Amendment used -- Mr. Justice Stewart's language in the Guest case.","start":2518.449,"stop":2526.02,"duration":7.57},{"text":"Now if Congress does implement the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment by passing some appropriate legislation such as the housing law, then perhaps, we have a serious constitutional question.","start":2526.02,"stop":2541.571,"duration":15.55},{"text":"I don't know.","start":2541.571,"stop":2542.083,"duration":0.51},{"text":"I would think in view of some of the recent opinions of this Court that such legislation probably would be upheld.","start":2542.083,"stop":2548.444,"duration":6.36},{"text":"But as I say I have not made a -- such a study of it that I seem competent --","start":2548.444,"stop":2553.654,"duration":5.21}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"It seems to me like you're arguing if you could not implement it, if you -- the legislative directly affecting an individual --","start":2553.654,"stop":2562.298,"duration":8.64}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I -- then I'm --","start":2562.298,"stop":2562.669,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think that you've got to look to the state.","start":2562.669,"stop":2565.073,"duration":2.4}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I'm sorry, then I've been misunderstood.","start":2565.073,"stop":2567.361,"duration":2.29},{"text":"I have not made myself plain, Your Honor.","start":2567.361,"stop":2570.161,"duration":2.8},{"text":"That is not what I --","start":2570.161,"stop":2570.9,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I had so understood as I (Voice Overlap) --","start":2570.9,"stop":2572.581,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"My argument as to that had to do with a piece of legislation that is already on the books.","start":2572.581,"stop":2577.464,"duration":4.88},{"text":"And what I am saying is not the Congress didn't have power at that time to have such legislation so worded that it would be aimed that individual action.","start":2577.464,"stop":2586.58,"duration":9.12},{"text":"What I'm saying is that when it did exercise its power in 1866, it did not aim at individual (Inaudible) this and I want to correct any impression that I may have made that --","start":2586.58,"stop":2598.997,"duration":12.42}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, referring back to Marsh, there was no statute in that case does it?","start":2598.997,"stop":2605.037,"duration":6.04}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"If Marsh versus Alabama?","start":2605.037,"stop":2606.201,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2606.201,"stop":2607.792,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that came under the Fourteenth Amendment because they were state actions --","start":2607.792,"stop":2611.758,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that is in the statute?","start":2611.758,"stop":2613.751,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"There was state action though.","start":2613.751,"stop":2615.267,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"I said statute.","start":2615.267,"stop":2616.505,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"But no statute there.","start":2616.505,"stop":2617.311,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"There was no statute there.","start":2617.311,"stop":2621.195,"duration":3.88},{"text":"Now, will you say there's no statute here?","start":2621.195,"stop":2623.704,"duration":2.51}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":2623.704,"stop":2624.889,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Now let me ask you --","start":2624.889,"stop":2625.495,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the Fourteenth Amendment.","start":2625.495,"stop":2626.354,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me ask you this.","start":2626.354,"stop":2630.384,"duration":4.03},{"text":"Is the right to distribute literature in a community like this entitled to a greater protection than the right to live and exist in the community?","start":2630.384,"stop":2646.534,"duration":16.15}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say that raises the question as to whether the rights under the First Amendment are any greater than the rights.","start":2646.534,"stop":2658.363,"duration":11.83},{"text":"But I suppose under the Fourteenth Amendment to buy a property or something like that or due process.","start":2658.363,"stop":2668.032,"duration":9.67},{"text":"It's a question of balancing values, the values of our democratic society.","start":2668.032,"stop":2675.927,"duration":7.89},{"text":"And I say that that question should be resolved by Congress, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":2675.927,"stop":2680.333,"duration":4.41}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"What right are you balancing against the right to live than exist?","start":2680.333,"stop":2685.973,"duration":5.64}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"The right of free speech or religion.","start":2685.973,"stop":2690.146,"duration":4.17}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is this -- your client claim the right to a free speech here, is that what you said?","start":2690.146,"stop":2695.606,"duration":5.46}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no.","start":2695.606,"stop":2695.825,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what are you balancing in this case?","start":2695.825,"stop":2697.195,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"What I'm saying -- what I'm --","start":2697.195,"stop":2698.611,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"In this case, what are you balancing?","start":2698.611,"stop":2700.712,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":2700.712,"stop":2701.348,"duration":0.64},{"text":"I didn't get what --","start":2701.348,"stop":2701.591,"duration":0.24}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"In this case what are you balancing?","start":2701.591,"stop":2705.12,"duration":3.53}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'm balancing -- I really was not balancing.","start":2705.12,"stop":2708.807,"duration":3.69},{"text":"I was trying to -- in this case, I was trying to say in reply to your question that if the problem is one determining which is more important, the right to distribute literature or the right to enjoy property properly by not having to live in segregated communities, by buying the house whenever the house is on the market without -- being prevented doing so by discriminatory conduct.","start":2708.807,"stop":2733.733,"duration":24.93},{"text":"If that is the problem, I say then you're dealing with policy making.","start":2733.733,"stop":2739.868,"duration":6.13},{"text":"I say that that is something for the legislature to determine rather than the Courts.","start":2739.868,"stop":2745.265,"duration":5.4},{"text":"In any event I say that as of this time, the legislature has not yet decided.","start":2745.265,"stop":2750.614,"duration":5.35},{"text":"It may if it passes a fair housing bill that that --","start":2750.614,"stop":2752.878,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Have decided that in Marsh either, does it?","start":2752.878,"stop":2756.657,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"It decided it as to --","start":2756.657,"stop":2758.549,"duration":1.89}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"The Congress?","start":2758.549,"stop":2759.399,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":2759.399,"stop":2760.153,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"The Congress hadn't decided it in Marsh either, did it?","start":2760.153,"stop":2764.05,"duration":3.9}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"In Marsh?","start":2764.05,"stop":2765.136,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2765.136,"stop":2766.101,"duration":0.97}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't quite understand your question how would the Congress --","start":2766.101,"stop":2768.09,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"There were no statute in Marsh, was there?","start":2768.09,"stop":2770.443,"duration":2.35},{"text":"It was decided on the (Voice Overlap) --","start":2770.443,"stop":2771.667,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Because there was clearly -- according to the Court, state action involved to the extent of the property that had been opened up for public use.","start":2771.667,"stop":2780.338,"duration":8.67},{"text":"This was the theory at Marsh.","start":2780.338,"stop":2781.837,"duration":1.5},{"text":"And that's why to Watchtower case distinguishes it.","start":2781.837,"stop":2784.39,"duration":2.55},{"text":"And it points out in its opinion --","start":2784.39,"stop":2785.272,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"You did not understand about Marsh, did you?","start":2785.272,"stop":2787.461,"duration":2.19},{"text":"I didn't.","start":2787.461,"stop":2788.448,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":2788.448,"stop":2789.02,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I say, you did not understand about the Marsh case, did you as I did not.","start":2789.02,"stop":2795.079,"duration":6.06},{"text":"That we we're holding anything except the Fourteenth Amendment didn't forbid it because there was state action.","start":2795.079,"stop":2804.06,"duration":8.98},{"text":"But we held was that there were state action.","start":2804.06,"stop":2806.762,"duration":2.7},{"text":"It was a town treated by the state as to any other city in the state and with the streets open and everything else.","start":2806.762,"stop":2815.304,"duration":8.54},{"text":"But we did not say that the Fourteenth Amendment guaranteed these people to have that right under any in all circumstances.","start":2815.304,"stop":2823.872,"duration":8.57},{"text":"It's a private ownership.","start":2823.872,"stop":2824.976,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":2824.976,"stop":2826.124,"duration":1.15},{"text":"And as a matter of fact, the New York Court of Appeals points that out immediately.","start":2826.124,"stop":2829.587,"duration":3.46},{"text":"It says Marsh's activities all took place on a sidewalk in Chickasaw Alabama, a company town.","start":2829.587,"stop":2835.736,"duration":6.15},{"text":"Then it goes on a point out, made it plain that a municipal corporation cannot ban the distribution of literature on its streets, sidewalks and public places so as public areas.","start":2835.736,"stop":2845.064,"duration":9.33},{"text":"And that is why I thought Mr. Justice Black, you kept saying in your opinion.","start":2845.064,"stop":2849.396,"duration":4.33},{"text":"I don't -- whether you repeated it but I know your famous language which has been quoted very often, that private property does become circumscribed by constitutional and other legal rights the moment it has been opened up for general use.","start":2849.396,"stop":2863.741,"duration":14.34}]},{"speakerName":"Abe Fortas","textObjs":[{"text":"But who kept them off the street in Marsh?","start":2863.741,"stop":2867.1,"duration":3.36}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"The owner, yes.","start":2867.1,"stop":2869.458,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And what makes -- what made it -- what characterize that town as representing some arm of the state, what was it that made it that way?","start":2869.458,"stop":2881.251,"duration":11.79}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think there's any question what that town did -- resemble a regular incorporated town just as (Voice Overlap) --","start":2881.251,"stop":2889.258,"duration":8.01}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"So, the acts of the owner who ran the town where the acts of the state.","start":2889.258,"stop":2895.212,"duration":5.95}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"That's in effect what we held, isn't it?","start":2895.212,"stop":2898.367,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Only as to the streets and sidewalks, Your Honors.","start":2898.367,"stop":2901.796,"duration":3.43},{"text":"That is my point.","start":2901.796,"stop":2903.478,"duration":1.68},{"text":"And let me -- it seems to be --Was it held that a state --","start":2903.478,"stop":2905.347,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I know --","start":2905.347,"stop":2906.136,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon?","start":2906.136,"stop":2907.084,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"The state couldn't disguise its operation by letting it be done by private owner in his name.","start":2907.084,"stop":2916.315,"duration":9.23}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't.","start":2916.315,"stop":2916.831,"duration":0.52},{"text":"Of course not.","start":2916.831,"stop":2917.328,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But we did not unhold that this was acting under the Fourteenth Amendment.","start":2917.328,"stop":2923.889,"duration":6.56},{"text":"We held that the Fourteenth Amendment didn't forbid it because of the nature of this property which has become to all intents and purposes an incorporated town in Alabama which was recognized as such by every agency of the state.","start":2923.889,"stop":2940.643,"duration":16.75}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"But a --","start":2940.643,"stop":2941.254,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I happen to know about Chickasaw --","start":2941.254,"stop":2942.711,"duration":1.46}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2942.711,"stop":2942.73,"duration":0.02}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"I've been there many times.","start":2942.73,"stop":2945.197,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"But Your Honor, it certainly did not hold that the constitutional prohibition would apply to every portion of the town of Chickasaw.","start":2945.197,"stop":2952.47,"duration":7.27}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Not even if he hold it --","start":2952.47,"stop":2952.606,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Even the private owner --","start":2952.606,"stop":2953.292,"duration":0.69}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"-- it would apply to every piece of private property.","start":2953.292,"stop":2956.616,"duration":3.32}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"When used or intended for general public use, that's their language.","start":2956.616,"stop":2961.128,"duration":4.51},{"text":"And that we agree with wholeheartedly.","start":2961.128,"stop":2963.111,"duration":1.98},{"text":"And that is the reason why on the Watchtower case, this very Court refused to grant --","start":2963.111,"stop":2966.522,"duration":3.41}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"But that of course does not answer your problems on this statute, does it?","start":2966.522,"stop":2972.395,"duration":5.87}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"On Section 1982?","start":2972.395,"stop":2973.594,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2973.594,"stop":2974.173,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no.","start":2974.173,"stop":2974.583,"duration":0.41},{"text":"Here, we're dealing with the Fourteenth Amendment.","start":2974.583,"stop":2976.144,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Dealing with the interpretation of the statute as to what Congress has said and what it's forbidden?","start":2976.144,"stop":2981.542,"duration":5.4}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"As to that claim, there are two claims in this case.","start":2981.542,"stop":2985.098,"duration":3.56},{"text":"One claim is based solely on 1962 independently the Fourteenth Amendment.","start":2985.098,"stop":2990.488,"duration":5.39},{"text":"The other is based solely on the First Section of the Fourteenth Amendment on the whole cloth of that Section without any kind of statutory stitching whatsoever.","start":2990.488,"stop":3002.419,"duration":11.93},{"text":"In its bare terms, I get -- I refer to the language of Mr. Justice Stewart in the Guest case, in its barest terms.","start":3002.419,"stop":3009.404,"duration":6.99},{"text":"And it is our position, if it please the Court, that until and unless the Fourteenth Amendment is implemented by appropriate legislation no right of action exists in this type of situation as against the (Inaudible).","start":3009.404,"stop":3028.462,"duration":19.06}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you --","start":3028.462,"stop":3029.119,"duration":0.66}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr.--","start":3029.119,"stop":3029.739,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you -- excuse me, go ahead.","start":3029.739,"stop":3030.897,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Hugo L. Black","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, go ahead, please.","start":3030.897,"stop":3032.902,"duration":2.01}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you tell me how -- let's assume for the moment that 1982 does cover the state and was directed at a private refusal to sell.","start":3032.902,"stop":3045.572,"duration":12.67},{"text":"Then how does the plaintiff get into the Court?","start":3045.572,"stop":3049.77,"duration":4.2}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice White --","start":3049.77,"stop":3050.211,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Under what statute?","start":3050.211,"stop":3050.997,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"You have asked another --","start":3050.997,"stop":3052.212,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Under what statute?","start":3052.212,"stop":3053.374,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"-- cutting question and it's a question that I have posed in my brief.","start":3053.374,"stop":3057.908,"duration":4.53},{"text":"I don't know.","start":3057.908,"stop":3058.671,"duration":0.76},{"text":"The Court will have to fashion some kind of a remedy for the plaintiff.","start":3058.671,"stop":3062.115,"duration":3.44}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the -- what's wrong with 1983?","start":3062.115,"stop":3064.475,"duration":2.36},{"text":"Because there you had -- do you have to find state action?","start":3064.475,"stop":3066.253,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Even the Government admits that that Section does not apply because it clearly says under color of law and it's a very distinction that Mr. Justice Fortas made in the Price case.","start":3066.253,"stop":3075.223,"duration":8.97},{"text":"Section 1943 is like Section 242, which Mr. Justice Fortas so enlighteningly I thought, (Voice Overlap) --","start":3075.223,"stop":3082.844,"duration":7.62}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but you can -- I suppose --","start":3082.844,"stop":3084.314,"duration":1.47}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"That was under color of law.","start":3084.314,"stop":3085.553,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose that this subdivision even if it wasn't so much so organized and so operated as to represent the state within the meaning of the Fourteenth Amendment in Marsh.","start":3085.553,"stop":3098.634,"duration":13.08},{"text":"Even if it weren't that, I suppose that you -- it would be possible to find the color of a state statute for purposes of 1983 just because if the authority in the statutes to organize this town, or to organize this --","start":3098.634,"stop":3117.25,"duration":18.62}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"But the Government doesn't --","start":3117.25,"stop":3118.205,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"-- subdivision, and to exercise these powers.","start":3118.205,"stop":3121.42,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Even the Government in its brief says that it admittedly that Section does not apply for purposes --","start":3121.42,"stop":3125.994,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"The Government's brief doesn't bind us, you know.","start":3125.994,"stop":3127.971,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Pardon.","start":3127.971,"stop":3128.335,"duration":0.36},{"text":"No.","start":3128.335,"stop":3130.286,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Trieman, who --","start":3130.286,"stop":3131.55,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think even the petitioners claim that, Mr. Justice White.","start":3131.55,"stop":3134.074,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"They don't bind this either?","start":3134.074,"stop":3135.743,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Treiman, who owns the water system that supplies this subdivision?","start":3135.743,"stop":3141.813,"duration":6.07}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"It comes from the county water company just as the other utilities come from public utilities.","start":3141.813,"stop":3148.656,"duration":6.84}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Public utilities?","start":3148.656,"stop":3148.856,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, and the complaint alleges that.","start":3148.856,"stop":3150.681,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it publicly owned utility?","start":3150.681,"stop":3153.497,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"They are -- no, I don't think so.","start":3153.497,"stop":3155.806,"duration":2.31},{"text":"They are privately owned but they're quasi public utilities and --","start":3155.806,"stop":3158.88,"duration":3.07}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Who owns --","start":3158.88,"stop":3159.287,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"-- regulated by the state.","start":3159.287,"stop":3160.512,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Who owns the sewer system?","start":3160.512,"stop":3163.151,"duration":2.64}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"That also is -- I think this particular subdivision is beyond the limits reached by the Saint Louis Metropolitan Sewer Agency.","start":3163.151,"stop":3173.052,"duration":9.9},{"text":"And so it is, I think, handled by a private sewer agency.","start":3173.052,"stop":3177.99,"duration":4.94},{"text":"And the subdevelop -- the subdivision developer has to build a trunk line to some sort of a treatment plant that is maintained by that sewer agency.","start":3177.99,"stop":3186.494,"duration":8.5},{"text":"And I think they can use some facilities of that sewer agency.","start":3186.494,"stop":3188.789,"duration":2.3}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Who furnishes the fire service system?","start":3188.789,"stop":3192.449,"duration":3.66}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"I would say that is done by -- what is the name of that -- there's an organization of communities that furnish --","start":3192.449,"stop":3200.538,"duration":8.09}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Public agency?","start":3200.538,"stop":3201.305,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3201.305,"stop":3202.46,"duration":1.16},{"text":"I don't deny that at all.","start":3202.46,"stop":3204.163,"duration":1.7},{"text":"Fire police protection, surely.","start":3204.163,"stop":3206.257,"duration":2.09}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Fire and police protection by the public?","start":3206.257,"stop":3208.386,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Israel Treiman","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, just as any other citizen.","start":3208.386,"stop":3211.898,"duration":3.51},{"text":"I, as a private homeowner, I don't have to be a subdivision developer to have that, those facilities available to me.","start":3211.898,"stop":3217.487,"duration":5.59},{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":3217.487,"stop":3218.231,"duration":0.74},{"text":"I've see the red light.","start":3218.231,"stop":3219.636,"duration":1.4},{"text":"Thank you for your patience.","start":3219.636,"stop":3226.389,"duration":6.75}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice --","start":3226.389,"stop":3227.316,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Liberman.","start":3227.316,"stop":3227.677,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"-- may it please the Court.","start":3227.677,"stop":3229.759,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you suggest to me how you do get in the Court if 1982 covers this?","start":3229.759,"stop":3236.045,"duration":6.29},{"text":"Do you need a separate remedy statute --","start":3236.045,"stop":3239.029,"duration":2.98}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I said --","start":3239.029,"stop":3239.112,"duration":0.08}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"(Voice Overlap) just walk in under the general jurisdictional --","start":3239.112,"stop":3242.102,"duration":2.99}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"I have three answers.","start":3242.102,"stop":3243.706,"duration":1.6},{"text":"And the first is that, I think that 1983 could cover under any customer usage of the state.","start":3243.706,"stop":3249.833,"duration":6.13},{"text":"I think perhaps a better statute would be Section 1988 which is derived from Section 3 of the Civil Rights Act of 1866 and specifically says that civil actions may get the remedy from the state common law as modified by statutes.","start":3249.833,"stop":3267.771,"duration":17.94},{"text":"Thirdly, I would say that regardless that there was any statute that Congress did not intend to create a right without a remedy in this situation.","start":3267.771,"stop":3275.968,"duration":8.2},{"text":"That this legislation was a result going back to the civil war perhaps at that time the bloodiest war ever fought in the history of mankind.","start":3275.968,"stop":3286.017,"duration":10.05},{"text":"And following the Thirteenth Amendment, (Inaudible) was enacted once, passed over the veto of President Johnson and then enacted the third time in 1870.","start":3286.017,"stop":3295.085,"duration":9.07},{"text":"And I think it's difficult to argue that Congress contended to merely create hollow words --","start":3295.085,"stop":3299.735,"duration":4.65}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what do you do, you come in and you just simply alleged jurisdiction and say this was within the equitable jurisdiction of the Court?","start":3299.735,"stop":3305.912,"duration":6.18}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"That's -- I think that would be the third ground that we --","start":3305.912,"stop":3308.752,"duration":2.84}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you know any cases like that?","start":3308.752,"stop":3310.917,"duration":2.16}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you rely on cases like Republic Steel I suppose?","start":3310.917,"stop":3313.74,"duration":2.82}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I really -- I wouldn't see what -- if any harder than somebody makes an illegal left turn and smacks in to me.","start":3313.74,"stop":3319.798,"duration":6.06},{"text":"I can file a suit and say it was negligent of him to make that left turn and get a judicial remedy even though the (Voice Overlap) --","start":3319.798,"stop":3326.231,"duration":6.43}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it may not be quite that simple but --","start":3326.231,"stop":3328.224,"duration":1.99}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel H. Liberman","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but in addition, I do think that there is a statutory authority for a civil remedy in the Court in this type of case.","start":3328.224,"stop":3341.884,"duration":13.66},{"text":"As to the interpretation of the statute, I wanted to go back briefly to the passages quoted from Mr. Treiman's brief.","start":3341.884,"stop":3350.626,"duration":8.74},{"text":"On page 15, you'll note that the quotation, the first both to laws barbaric and treatment inhumane are the words meted out by our white enemies to our colored friends, obviously referring to both state law and private action.","start":3350.626,"stop":3365.572,"duration":14.95},{"text":"Across the page on page 14, I think the quote is obviously referring in Section 2 of the Civil Rights Act of 1866, which is limited, done or a color of state law.","start":3365.572,"stop":3376.276,"duration":10.7},{"text":"But that limitation -- the Congress knew how to make and made it in much legislation and left it out in the Section 1 and Section 3.","start":3376.276,"stop":3384.242,"duration":7.97},{"text":"So, that I think you can fairly interpret their intention as living it out intentionally when they didn't mean for it to be there.","start":3384.242,"stop":3393.889,"duration":9.65},{"text":"This legislation unlike the prior Freedmen's Bureau Bill applied to all states not just to the states which had been in rebellion.","start":3393.889,"stop":3402.896,"duration":9.01},{"text":"And I think that it was aimed at the results and the holding of this Court in Scott versus Sanford.","start":3402.896,"stop":3410.586,"duration":7.69},{"text":"To some extent, it was not just to wipe out inimical state laws.","start":3410.586,"stop":3415.532,"duration":4.95},{"text":"It was to grant the rights to which people were entitled regardless of whether the particular state they were in had a law that would've limited that right or not as applied everywhere.","start":3415.532,"stop":3426.622,"duration":11.09},{"text":"So that -- so our contention that the law -- we don't argue that it would overwrite any state law to the contrary because it says right at the end, any law statute ordinance regulation accustomed to the contrary not withstanding.","start":3426.622,"stop":3442.174,"duration":15.55},{"text":"But we think it had a broader purpose as well.","start":3442.174,"stop":3446.518,"duration":4.34},{"text":"If it were only attempting to remove a certain disqualifications, I think this would've been accomplished by the constitutional amendments anyway.","start":3446.518,"stop":3455.333,"duration":8.82},{"text":"But it also would've been accomplished by the other parts of Section 1 of that Act, which gave all persons the equal right to make enforced contracts, to sue and be parties, give evidence in Court.","start":3455.333,"stop":3467.415,"duration":12.08},{"text":"And to the same -- fall on equal benefit of all laws and proceedings by the security of persons and properties.","start":3467.415,"stop":3473.275,"duration":5.86},{"text":"So, I think that language alone would've remove any disqualification whether by state law or otherwise and that when they go on to say, shall have the same right to inherit, and to purchase and to lease.","start":3473.275,"stop":3486.023,"duration":12.75},{"text":"That they meant that he would have the substantive right, the same right as is enjoyed by all other citizens.","start":3486.023,"stop":3492.545,"duration":6.52},{"text":"And if this was the interpretation which Congress had and which is the only fair interpretation on the basis of the language of the statute.","start":3492.545,"stop":3503.228,"duration":10.68}]},{"speakerName":"Earl Warren","textObjs":[{"text":"Very well.","start":3503.228,"stop":3506.606,"duration":3.38}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Warren Court","arguedOn":"Apr  1 - 2, 1968","petitioner":"Jones","respondent":"Alfred H. Mayer Company","docket":"645","citation":"392 US 409 (1968)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/392/409","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 17, 1968"}